<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: France Not to Take Side in Congo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Vaillant, French minister
for relations with parliament, said Wednesday that France will not
take sides in the on-going war in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to what could be said, France does not interfere or
express its preference. France does not choose camps or play a
particular or partisan role in this affair," he said.
</P>
<P>
But France wishes to see the emergence in the region,
particularly in ex-Zaire, of a "respectable but not Ubuesque
government that has a form of legitimacy, knows how to listen to
the people and to take them into account," he said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin as saying on
Wednesday that France hopes some "real governments" would come up
in the Great Lakes region of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Jospin told a cabinet meeting that if real governments could
emerge in that region, it would be "a gleam of hope," said
Vaillant.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister and the government hope that an
international action can exert pressure so that in this region,
solid, serious, respectable governments that know how to listen
to the people and preserve the population, could become the
reality," Vaillant said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that France is worried about outside
interference and "overlapping" of difference forces in the
Great Lakes region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
