<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Not to Support Intervention in Congo: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Botswana was adopting a
wait-and-see attitude over events in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC), and was unlikely to support any military action
against rebel forces there, an official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The situation of the DRC versus the 14-member states of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) was confusing,
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Botswana's
permanent secretary for foreign affairs, Ernest Mpofu, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Botswana had not been involved in events to date. It had been
invited to a meeting in Zimbabwe on Tuesday at which a decision
was taken to sent assistance to DRC President Laurent Kabila, but
had attended only at ambassadorial level, Mpofu said.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was taken without us."
</P>
<P>
"There was no way our representative could have committed
himself. We would not want any SADC country to become involved in
the take-over of the government... by force."
</P>
<P>
He said the best solution would not necessarily be
intervention by a regional force, but by international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"I doubt if we would want to be involved. With such a complex
situation the best thing is to involve the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"Botswana has been involved in peace-keeping exercises before,
but I am not sure that this is a peace-keeping exercise," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
