<HEADLINE> Chinese Flood Coping With Life in Temporary Shelters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Though millions of Chinese flood
victims are homeless, their basic daily needs have been ensured,
according to government officials.
</P>
<P>
More than 470,000 residents in Qiqihar, a heavy industrial
center in northernmost Heilongjiang Province, were evacuated
before floods reached their hometown, according to a city official.
</P>
<P>
Most of those evacuated are either living with relatives or
sharing the homes of strangers in urban areas, the Qiqihar
official said. Some 120,000 have built temporary shelters in the
open country, he said, adding that they are living a normal life
and remain calm.
</P>
<P>
The flood relief headquarters in Qiqihar has set up six special
groups to take charge of such duties as collecting relief
materials, transportation, disease prevention and public
security. These groups have distributed 6.26 million yuan of
grain, edible oil, plastic sheeting, clothing and medicine to
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The city's industrial and commercial department has provided
3,100 tons of steamed buns daily since Aug. 12 to flood-affected
areas and ordered the quick production of 1,000 cotton quilts, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Haisheng, mayor of Qiqihar, on Monday visited 290
households in temporary shelters built on the three hills outside
Banla Village. He met with the displaced people and inquired about
their lives. The mayor also delivered 50 tons of dried noodles and
200 gas stoves, and promised to bring them more dried noodles,
edible oil, salt and stoves.
</P>
<P>
One middle-aged woman tearfully said that she is grateful to
the Communist Party and the government. When the flood recedes,
she said, she and her fellow villagers will sell more grain to the
state to return their thanks.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the government of Yueyang, where the
Yangtze meets the Dongting Lake, has delivered 700 tons of rice,
110,000 articles of clothing and 7 million yuan of medicine to
flooded areas, according to a local civil service official.
</P>
<P>
All 220,000 local people stranded by floods have been evacuated
to safer places, the official said, adding that their daily meals
include rice, vegetables and meat. Drinking water has been shipped
from other parts of China, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Medical centers and toilet facilities have been set up near the
shelters, said Zhou Changgong, mayor of Yueyang. Doctors from
Beijing are treating 700 patients a day while visiting the
temporary shelters, the mayor said. The city also sent 487 medical
teams to patrol the Yangtze embankments, he said.
</P>
<P>
Medical teams have inoculated 50,000 flood victims against
disease and distributed snail fever medicine to 600,000 people,
Zhou said, adding that their efforts have helped curb the spread
of intestinal infectious diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
