<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Punish Officials Responsible for Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali said on Wednesday that any officials who are
found responsible for the July tap water pollution in the capital
will be punished.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official news agency Petra quoted Majali as
saying that the punitive measures would be taken after he studies
the investigation report presented to him Wednesday by a special
committee that investigated the pollution.
</P>
<P>
The special commission was formed by the government on August 4
to see into the water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Majali did not reveal the contents of the 100-page report
presented by the committee, but he said that it contained "lengthy
and accurate" details of the incident.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would handle the issue "very attentively"
according to the directives of King Hussein and Crown Prince
Hassan.
</P>
<P>
In early July, the tap water in western part of the capital
became foul-smelling and murky, leading to the hospitalization of
some residents who suffered from diarrhea and nausea-related
diseases after drinking the water.
</P>
<P>
This caused panic and sparked widespread protests from the
residents, the parliament and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Water and Irrigation Munther Haddadin resigned on
August 10 to shoulder the responsibility for the pollution. And
Majali himself has also offered resignation due to the pollution
incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
