<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Faces Daunting Flood-Control Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- This capital of central China's
Hubei Province now faces a daunting task in flood control as the
water level of the part of Yangtze River running through the city
reached new heights.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the Yangtze River measured at Wuhan Pass in
Wuhan was 29.41 meters at 8 p.m. today, 1.13 meters higher than
the official warning line.
</P>
<P>
The latest water level, which rose by 0.13 meters between
Tuesday night and tonight, is also two centimeters higher than the
second all-time high reported earlier this month when the fourth
flood crest passed through Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
An official forecast by the Yangtze River Water Resources
Committee said that the water level is expected to rise to 29.47
meters, the highest this year, when the sixth flood crest passes
through Wuhan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze's water flow reached 72,100 cubic meters per second
at 8 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
The flood-control headquarters of Wuhan tonight ordered a
closer watch of the flood situation and warned that the major
embankment must be protected at all cost.
</P>
<P>
More than 180,000 civilians and soldiers are working to protect
the major embankment, while another 80,000 people have been
mobilized and more than 2,000 vehicles and 100 vessels are
prepared to fight against flooding risks.
</P>
<P>
In a similar development, flooding of Dongting Lake, one of
China's two major lakes in central Hunan Province, worsened today
as a result of the arrival of the sixth flood crest of the Yangtze
River and of renewed torrential rains in the valleys of two local
rivers.
</P>
<P>
The water level along a 1,500-kilometer-long embankment of the
lake today exceeded the historic high.
</P>
<P>
Some 13,500 people of the military forces have been dispatched
to the endangered sections of the embankment to counter floods,
raising to nearly 30,000 the number of officers and soldiers
fighting floods in the lake area, according to a provincial
official.
</P>
<P>
To guard against the worst possibilities, all old, physically
weak, sick and handicapped people were relocated to safety by the
start of today, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
