<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Bank Bails out Local Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
Wednesday came into the market to save the Zimbabwean Dollar
which had come under renewed pressure from importers.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Foreign Exchange Association of Zimbabwe
Zibusiso Nkomo said that the pressure on the local currency began
Tuesday and went on until Wednesday morning when the central bank
intervened.
</P>
<P>
"It is being caused by demand," Nkomo said, "The importers are
back."
</P>
<P>
At one time the Zimbabwean Dollar was trading at between 21.85
and 22.85 to the U.S. Dollar but the reserve bank's intervention
saw it coming down to 20.80 and 22.10.
</P>
<P>
"That is where it closed at today. In other words, the
intervention has assisted... I do not know what will happen
tomorrow," the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Nkomo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The local unit fell by 12.5 percent against the U.S. Dollar
two weeks ago and traders blamed the central bank for failing to
come into the market on time.
</P>
<P>
But the Reserve Bank said that the Zimbabwean Dollar had been
attacked by speculators and hiked the rediscount rate by three
percentage points to defend it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
