<HEADLINE> Britain Leads World in CD Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Despite comparatively higher
prices than elsewhere, people in Britain spend more on compact
discs than any other nation, according to the latest figures
compiled by the music industry, which shows that the average
Briton buys four albums a year.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that consumers in Europe are buying more
European music than ever before. Although the European market is
growing more slowly than other countries, Europe still represents
a third of all music sales in the world, according to the
International Federation of the Phonographic Industry.
</P>
<P>
Figures also showed that more and more Europeans are buying
homegrown tunes - 42 percent of sales in the past year were by
European artists, the highest-ever level.
</P>
<P>
Last month the UK's Consumers' Association magazine revealed
that CDs in Britain cost far more than those sold in other
countries. However, this has not deterred millions of Britain's
"die-hard music fans", local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The IFPI reports that while Europeans spend three times more
per head on music than the average around the world, Britons shell

