<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Leader Hails Egypt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A leading Sudanese opposition
leader Wednesday hailed Egypt's intensified efforts to mediate
between the Khartoum government and opposition parties in a bid to
end the 15-year civil war in its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak el-Mahdi, secretary general of the Sudanese National
Democratic Alliance (NDA) told a press conference here that said
Cairo's active involvement has lent an "African, Arab dimension
to" the current mediation efforts to end the fighting in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrea-based NDA, which groups all opposition factions
from northern and southern Sudan, held a three-day meeting here
under the host of Egypt since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Egypt, which is at odds with the
Khartoum government over border dispute, has hosted such meeting.
Egypt has accused Sudan of harboring Muslim militants and demanded
the extradition of the Sudanese suspects involved in the
assassination attempt on Mubarak in Addis Ababa in 1995.
</P>
<P>
But Khartoum charged Cairo for interfering in its internal
affair for hosting its opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is raising profile of its involvement," said Mahdi, who
underscored the importance of Egyptian role in ending the Sudanese
conflict and its bearing on Egypt's national security.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has kept a low profile in the Sudanese conflict but is
apparently adjusting the stance as fighting between the Sudanese
government and rebels is escalating and the famine crisis in
southern Sudan deepening.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with major Sudanese opposition leaders last
Wednesday, Mubarak reiterated the necessity of ending fightings
and urged the Sudanese leadership to exert serious efforts to
attain Sudan's territorial integrity and unity.
</P>
<P>
The war between the government troops and rebels forces
fighting for autonomy in southern Sudan, combined with famine, has
claimed over 1.5 million lives since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi, renewing the opposition's commitment to maintaining
Sudan's unity and territorial integrity, urged more neighboring
countries to join the "unified mediation efforts" led by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
But he said Egypt should cooperate with other concerned
countries and work through the framework of the Inter-governmental
Authority for Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
The latest NDA conference in Cairo was held after the collapse
of the initiative made by the IGAD to arrange a reconciliation
between the Khartoum government and the opposition alliance during
talks in Ethiopia early this month.
</P>
<P>
The second NDA meeting is slated for September 26 in Asmara,
Eritrea, to resume discussions and preparation for a statement
on the future of Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
