<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat rebutted Wednesday the statement made by a senior
Israeli minister that Israel has accepted the U.S. initiative
calling for a 13 percent West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Erekat was quoted by the Voice of Palestine radio as saying
that that it was not true that Israel will soon reach an
agreement with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) on Israeli
troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the remarks made Tuesday by the hawkish
Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon that Israel
has agreed to implement the U.S. plan and withdraw from an
additional 13 percent of the West bank.
</P>
<P>
Sharon revealed that Israeli government, against his
opposition, had also decided to carry out a further 1 percent West
Bank pullback in the third and last stage of redeployment. But he
blamed the Palestinians for simply seeking excuses to refuse to
sign a redeployment agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said all these statements were "maneuvers and games."
</P>
<P>
"All these statements are part of Israeli internal
disagreements on troop redeployment and aimed only at scoring
points," Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
He said he still refused to resume talks with the Israeli side
who continues its disrespect to the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The PNA and Israel resumed direct talks on the West Bank
redeployment on July 19, but have failed to produce concrete
results so far due to the dispute over the content of the next
pullback.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Israeli side proposed to have a 13
percent withdrawal, 3 percent of which should be made nature
reserves where the Palestinians could neither police nor build.
</P>
<P>
This proposal was rejected by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
communication director, said on Tuesday that Israel was still
interested in the nature reserve concept. 
</P>
</TEXT>
