<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria Hold Oil Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rasheed held talks here Wednesday with his visiting
Syrian counterpart Mohammed Mohammed Mahir Jamal to discuss
enhancing cooperation in the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers mainly discussed the executive plans of the
joint agreement on oil cooperation that was signed in last July
during Rasheed's Damascus trip.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two sides agreed to reopen the
pipelines from Iraq's northern oil fields in Kirkuk to the Syrian
port city Banias, and to construct a new pipeline with greater
capacity to meet Iraq's exporting requirements in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister and his delegation arrived in Baghdad
Tuesday afternoon for a three-day visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in 18 years that a Syrian oil minister
has paid an official visit to Iraq. During the Iran-Iraq War
between 1980 and 1988), Syria sided with Iran.
</P>
<P>
After their talks, Rasheed said that the date for resuming the
exports of Iraqi oil via the Syrian Port of Banias had not yet
fixed.
</P>
<P>
The United States has expressed opposition to the Iraqi-Syrian
agreement on the reopening and construction of pipelines, saying
the agreement should have the approval of the U.N. Sanctions
Committee first.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Iraqi Finance Minister Hikmat al-Azzawi also
met the Syrian minister and discussed means of further developing
bilateral economic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
