<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Regional Split over Military Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
Wednesday appeared to be divided over military assistance to the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to help it end the turmoil in
the third biggest central African country in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe said Wednesday that the Southern African Development
Community (SADC), the 14-nation regional economic bloc, would
provide military aid to DRC President Laurent Kabila to fight
against the rebels, who Kabila claims are backed by Rwanda and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
This was contradictory to gestures of South Africa, which is
currently busy maneuvering a possible political solution to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and Defense Minister
Joe Modise are on the second day of a peace-seeking mission to
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Nzo told British Broadcasting Corporation that "we are not
thinking in terms of any intervention force at the moment."
</P>
<P>
The situation in the DRC is worsening rapidly as the Tutsi-led
rebels advance closer to capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"All the political forces should be brought together to look
at how to bring about a stable political solution in that
country," said the South African foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Nzo and Modise were expected to discuss with the Rwandan and
Ugandan governments about the charges of invasion made by Kabila,
as well as "broader problems in that area."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven Mahachi said on Zimbabwe's
state radio Wednesday that southern African countries agreed
unanimously to send troops and arms to help Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi's statement followed a meeting Tuesday in Harare,
where defense ministers and high commissioners from nine of the
SADC members discussed the situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the rebel force is supported from
Uganda and Rwanda," Mahachi said. "It became very clear to us
that our sister country (Democratic Congo) has been invaded.
Therefore, we have to support the appeal for assistance."
</P>
<P>
The DRC was accepted as the 14th member of the SADC last year,
largely at Zimbabwe's insistence.
</P>
<P>
"It was unanimously agreed that we must, with urgency, make
sure practical assistance, both material and manpower, is given
to the DRC in order to restore peace and stability," Mahachi
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the people of (Democratic) Congo
support President Kabila," Mahachi said. "We are convinced that
our intention is to stop the fighting."
</P>
<P>
But he said no decision had been taken on what strengths would
be sent into the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Hours earlier, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe announced
that the SADC would help the DRC overcome rebel forces wishing to
oust Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's announcement of a general SADC agreement on
military intervention was considered to be rather quick as no
SADC summit had been held on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday meeting was reportedly attended only by four full
defense ministers, from Zimbabwe, Zambia, Namibia and Mozambique
apart from Congo. Also present were Angola's deputy defense
minister, high commissioners of Botswana and Tanzania, and South
Africa's deputy high commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's Permanent Secretary for Foreign Affairs Ernest
Mpofu, who was invited to the meeting in Harare, said Wednesday
that the decision on military aid to Democratic Congo was taken
without consulting Botswanan representatives.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was taken without us," Mpofu said. "There was no
way our representative could have committed himself."
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela, who chairs the SADC,
said in Johannesburg Wednesday that Pretoria did not refer to any
decision to provide military aid to the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He said former Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere phoned him
Tuesday and made certain appeals to him. "I will now be
discussing it with other heads of state," he said, declining to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, South African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad
made it clear that his country did not believe a military
solution was possible. He called for restraint in the actions of
the fighting sections in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Botswana said it was adopting a wait-and-see
attitude, but was unlikely to support military action against the
rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
