<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians' Real Income Down 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Russians' real income, or
after-tax income adjusted for inflation, during the first seven
months went down by 8.9 percent as compared with the same period
last year, the State Statistics Committee said.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend is set to pick up in the coming months as a
devalued ruble pushes prices up and fuels inflation, observers
say.
</P>
<P>
The nominal income, or the residents' pre-tax income without
inflation adjustment, fell 1.6 percent, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The average money income in July was 906.6 rubles (about 130
U.S. dollars according to the latest official exchange rate), 4
percent down from July 1997. If inflation and mandatory payments
were considered, the real money income last month dropped 8.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
About 32.1 million people, or 21.8 percent of the total
population, were living below subsistence level last month, up
from July 1997's 29.8 million people, or 20.2 percent of total
population.
</P>
<P>
The latest monthly subsistence wage, which changes from month
to month, was 438 rubles (about 63 dollars) in July. The average
monthly subsistence wage in January-July was 430 rubles (61.5
dollars) against 412 rubles (59 dollars) of the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russia's wage arrears totalled 75,844
million rubles (10,850 million dollars) in 10 basic industries on
August 1, up 6.5 percent from the beginning of July, the State
Statistics Committee said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Unpaid wages increased 4.4 percent in the production industries
and 14.9 percent in the social sphere.
</P>
<P>
The debt consists of amounts to be paid from the state budget
and by the enterprises, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The sharpest increases in wage arrears was registered in the
public health, culture and arts, and the education sectors, at
33.9 percent, 28.4 percent and 16.6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The lower standard of living for the Russians would fuel
discontent and threaten social stability, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey taken in mid-August, 65 percent of
Russians believed the government, in implementing reforms, "can no
longer count on people's patience," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear if the survey was taken before or after August
17, the day when the government raised the ceiling of the ruble
exchange corridor to 9.5 rubles to the dollar from 6.3 rubles to
the dollar. Nor was it known how many people were polled in the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Nugzar Betaneli, director of the Sociology and Parliamentarism
Institute which conducted the poll, said the number of Russians
"inclined to express their protest in some form" was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Twelve percent of the respondents expressed readiness to join
strikes, 11 percent would take part in armed insurrection, 8
percent would block automobile and railroads and 6 percent might
choose to seize enterprises, organizations and offices, the poll
results show.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 43 percent of the respondents said they support the
recent railroad blockades by coal miners in the Urals and Siberia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 44 percent of those polled said they view Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko's performance "rather negatively". Only
27 percent of those surveyed saw his activity "rather positively".
</P>
<P>
Only 8 percent of the respondents believe the government's
stabilization program would "improve the economic situation" as
against 37 who said "it would fail to make any impact on the
economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Deeply Concerned Over DRC: Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union expressed on
Wednesday its concern over the humanitarian situation in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Austria that is serving the rotating
presidency of the 15-nation union, said that the union is "deeply
concerned by the ongoing crisis in the DRC".
</P>
<P>
The union, the statement added, was particularly alarmed by
reports on human rights abuses in the African country.
</P>
<P>
"These reports credibly allege rounding-up, detention, beating,
torture, ethnic propaganda including hate radio broadcasts and in
some cases summary execution of Tutsis and possibly civilians of
other ethnic groups by authorities of the DRC," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The European Union strongly condemned all violations of human
rights and international humanitarian law and urged all parties to
the conflict to take the necessary measures to prevent such
violations and urged security forces to abstain from inciting
ethnic hatred in order to avoid the expansion of the human rights
violations in the region.
</P>
<P>
The union reiterated its support for the principles of
territorial integrity and respect for the sovereignty of the DRC
as well as for its appeal for peaceful solutions to the current
problems so that the process of reconstruction and democratization
can proceed.
</P>
<P>
The central and eastern European countries and Cyprus expressed
their alignment with the stance of the European Union. These
countries are applying for membership of the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
