<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says to Continue Bid for Iranians' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Wednesday promised
Iran that it would continue its efforts to help secure the release
of the Iranian nationals held by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani ambassador to Iran Javid Husain met with Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi and submitted a written message from
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. No detail of the content
available.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Husain briefed
Kharrazi on Islamabad's efforts in seeking the Iranians' release
from the hands of the Taliban forces.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi expressed dissatisfaction with Islamabad's
"insufficient efforts" and said Pakistan should adopt more serious
measures in view of its "high influence" on the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is believed to have been supporting the Taliban
militia in its swift rise to prominence and sweeping victory over
the opposition Northern Alliances, reportedly supported by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that a few days prior to Taliban's conquest of
Mazar-e-Sharif, the main stronghold of the opposition forces in
northern Afghanistan, Iran had officially called on Pakistani
government to secure guarantees from the Taliban on the safety of
Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Following contacts with the Taliban, the Pakistani government
gave Iran necessary assurances about the security and safety of
Iranians at the consulate office in the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Iranian diplomats, an IRNA correspondent and 35 drivers
were reported captured by Taliban forces storming into the city on
August 8. The Taliban conceded that it had arrested 35 Iranian
drivers, but said it had no information about the whereabouts of
the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi warned that the issue, if continued, would undoubtedly
leave negative impacts on Tehran-Islamabad ties.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has been putting even greater pressure on Pakistan to
seek an early release of its nationals through diplomatic
channels. But to achieve that goal it also vowed to take "every
action it deems necessary." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
