<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Against Turkey's Arms Build-up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Wednesday protested
against what it called Turkey's military build-up in the
Turkish-Cypriot controlled north of the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry's Permanent Secretary Alecos Shiambos made oral
representations to the ambassadors or charges d'affaires of the five
United Nations Security Council permanent members of Britain,
China, France, Russia and the United States in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
He showed the diplomats concrete evidences to back the case, an
official press release said.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou said on Monday that
the Turkish troops in northern Cyprus last week received 50 more
tanks and heavy artillery pieces, which have been deployed in
attack formation.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot government spokesman Christos Stylianides said on
Tuesday that Turkey has been stepping up its military presence in
northern Cyprus since last summer.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only
recognized by Ankara. Turkey is maintaining more than 35,000
troops there to allegedly protect the Turkish Cypriot minorities.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot-dominated Cypriot government, which is
internationally recognized, maintains a 14,500-strong armed
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
