<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angola, Russia Resume Military Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A Russian delegation of
ministers headed by Defense Minister Igor Sergueev has signed a
series of pacts on resuming military cooperation with Angola
during their brief tour to Luanda.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements reached by the two sides on the
cooperation in military technologies, the two states will
establish mixed defense industries so as to help maintain the
weaponry and to transfer military technologies.
</P>
<P>
Russia has agreed to train officers for Angola in order to
improve the battling capacity of the Angolan troops.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation in military technologies should be made the
locomotive of the cooperation in economy and finance," Sergueev
noted.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Defense Minister Pedro Sebastiao explained that most
of the weapons his troops use have come from Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said Angola should have its arms industries since there are
such joint arms industries in Angola's neighboring countries,
namely the Democratic Republic of Congo, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Sebastiao also said that Angola's debt of two billion U.S.
Dollars to Russia will not affect the military cooperation
between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Angola's debt to Russia resulted from purchasing weapons from
the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Prime Minister
Franca van-Dunem respectively held talks with the Russian
ministers of defense, fishery, petroleum, and geology and mines.
</P>
<P>
The visit of Russian ministers was aimed at furthering the
traditional friendly relationship between the two nations. In
June this year, President Dos Santos paid a visit to Moscow,
mending the fence with Russia which had backed its war against
UNITA in the 70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
During the visit which ended Tuesday, the Russian delegation
also signed with their Angolan counterparts protocols of intent
on resuming cooperation in petroleum and fishery. They have
agreed to submit the issue to the binational mixed commission to
convene in Moscow in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Noticeably, the Russian ministers came here as the Angolan
peace process has fallen into the most serious crisis in four
years and the Tutsi-led rebels in eastern part of the Democratic
Republic of Congo are pushing toward the capital Kinshasa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges World Intervention in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Wednesday urged the international community to intervene
and address the threat to peace and security if the Mideast peace
process collapses.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said in an interview that the peace process is a serious
international issue that has gone beyond a regional crisis, due to
the negative stance of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Such negative attitude is reflected in Israel's rejection of
all means to break the deadlock in peace talks, including the
Franco-Egyptian idea of holding an international peace conference
to rescue peace, and an American proposal on West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"But in spite of Israel's balking at a lukewarm American
intervention and other proposals, we must pursue the effort to
make the Egyptian-French initiative a reality," he urged.
</P>
<P>
The joint initiative put forward by Egypt and France came as
Washington failed to persuade Israel to accept its proposal on a
further Israeli withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the West Bank in
return for better Palestinian security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Moussa went to Paris last month to thrash out the details of
the proposed international conference, which might in the first
stage involves the U.S., the European Union, and other parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
This initiative does not make it a condition that the parties
directly concerned with the peace process - Israel, Syria and the
Palestinians - should attend, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
It was only one day ago that Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat told Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
during a meeting in Egypt's Mediterranean resort of Mersa Matrouh
that he was frustrated with the failure of Washington to sell its
peace proposal to Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted the American idea and is waiting
for a yes from Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Arafat also discuss means to implement the
Franco-Egyptian initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks were frozen over Israel's
settlement expansion in Arab East Jerusalem and long delays in
troop redeployment. The recent direct contacts between the two
sides fail to make a breakthrough. 
</P>
