<HEADLINE> Islamic Organization Urges World Efforts to Save </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) Wednesday called on the world community
to employ greater efforts to revive the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The OIC made the call in a statement issued by its Secretary
General Ezzidine Laraki at the OIC headquarters in Jeddah, Saudi
Arabia, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The OIC appealed to the international community to shoulder its
responsibility to salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and its two neighbors Syria and
Lebanon has broken down in early 1996 due to the dispute over the
future of the Golan Heights that Israel captured from Syria in the
1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have also been deadlocked
since March 1997 after the Jewish state began construction of a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians
want as the capital of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The talks are currently stuck over the long overdue Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The OIC accused the Israeli government of obstructing the peace
process by resorting to hard-line policy on the peace talks and
plans to judaize Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic organization called for additional efforts to
pressure Israel into carrying out the relevant United Nations
resolutions on the Arab-Israeli conflicts and the status of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It urged U.N. member states to support the Palestinian people
in their struggle to regain their legitimate rights, including the
establishment of their own state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
