to a press release from the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
They are said to have held consultative discussions on the
current situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Zimbabwe said the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) will provide military aid to DRC President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
As head of the SADC, South African President Nelson Mandela
said the 14-member regional economic bloc is not considering to
help Kabila militarily, adding that he is still pursuing a
peaceful solution to the worsening situation in Congo (k),the
third largest central African country.
</P>
<P>
The situation in DRC deteriorated on August 2 when Tutsi
soldiers in eastern Congo (K) started rebellion against the
Kabila government following his order that Rwandan army return
home. The fighting between the government army and the
Banyamulenge soldiers quickly spread to eastern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the rebel Tutsi soldiers claimed that they had
occupied one third of the country and taken Matadi, a city which
serves as the lifeline for the capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila blamed the rebellion on neighboring Rwanda and Uganda,
both of which quickly denied.
</P>
<P>
On the deterioration in DRC, southern African countries tend
to adopt widely different attitudes. Some prefer to back Kabila
while others tend to be behind the Tutsi soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Museveni has recently held many discussions on the matter with
foreign delegations and envoys of regional as well as
international organizations. 
</P>
