<HEADLINE> UN Takes Steps to Speed Up Iraq's Oil Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations had
recruited two oil experts from Dutch Saybolt firm to help speed up
Iraq's order, receiving and installation of oil equipment, U.N.
spokesman said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council of the United Nations last May authorized
Iraq to sell 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil during the
subsequent six months, the so-called new U.N. oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq complained that it did not have the capacity to export
such an amount of oil due to its shabby oil equipment. The Council
last June agreed to allow Iraq to export 300 million U.S. dollars
worth of spare parts to ungrade its dilapidated oil industry.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the two experts would provide
information on the contracts to the Security Council's Sanctions
Committee on Iraq in an effort to speed up the processing of
contracts for spare parts for Iraq's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said the Council's sanctions committee had received 55
contracts it needed to approve as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Saybolt, an oil industry consulting firm in the Netherlands,
has advised the United Nations to endorse Iraq's request for a
minimum of 300 U.S. dollars worth of oil equipment to meet the oil
export targets under the new U.N. oil-for-food program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
