<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Respond to Teachers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia National Union of
Teachers (ZNUT) appealed to the government Wednesday to respond
quickly to the plight of the untrained teachers working in the
country's remote areas.
</P>
<P>
All untrained teachers manning some schools in remote areas
have not received their salaries for the last eight months, Roy
Mwaba, a ZNUT official, said in a statement released in Lusaka,
according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The ZNUT, said Mwaba, wishes to condemn the government's
attitude and insensitivity over the plight of the untrained
teachers countrywide since the government has done nothing to
pay the teachers, forcing most of them to desert their homes in
search food.
</P>
<P>
He described the government's attitude as "immoral" and a
violation of human rights for workers to go for eight months
without being paid their dues in a Christian nation like Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The government is setting a bad precedent to other employers
in the country to start treating their workers in the same way,
Mwaba said.
</P>
<P>
He also deplored the conditions in some schools in remote
areas which are being manned by very few untrained teachers with
no teaching materials and therefore with poor results.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the union showed that some schools depend
almost entirely on the services of untrained teachers.
</P>
<P>
Mwaba wondered how pupils in examination classes would pass
their examinations, especially in schools being run by only a
head teacher and a single teacher, which is the usual case in the
country's remote areas. 
</P>
