<HEADLINE> Iran's Bill to Raise Electorate Age Opposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderates on Wednesday
voiced strong opposition to a bill proposed by the conservatives
to raise the minimum electorate age from 15 to 16.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Party of Constructive Executives (CEI),
which groups close allies of President Mohammad Khatami, called on
the Majlis (parliament) to drop the bill, which has been approved
by the legislature's commission for Domestic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
It is important for the youth to participate in the third
election of the Experts Assembly slated for October 23, which has
the power to determine the country's supreme leader, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The young people, together with intellectuals and women, played
a decisive role in Khatami's landslide victory in the May 1997
presidential election over his conservative rival, the Majlis
speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri.
</P>
<P>
The CEI said that 15 is considered as the age of maturity in
the religion of Islam and that by raising the age limit, the
conservatives would be contented to see some 1 million young
people deprived of the right to vote for the country's future.
</P>
<P>
The young generation, born after the 1979 Islamic Revolution
which brought the rule of the clergymen, make up more than 50
percent of the country's population.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed on the eve of the sensitive election of the
Experts Assembly, is seen as a ploy to prevent the moderates from
being elected into the powerful body.
</P>
<P>
To break the conservatives' monopoly of power, the moderates
also have to seek a change in the Guardians Council, which has
been empowered by the election law to screen and thus decide the
qualification of candidates for any elections.
</P>
<P>
The CEI called on different groups to refrain from restricting
the Experts Assembly to factional monopoly, and the Guardians
Council to execute its power impartially.
</P>
<P>
The conservative-dominated council has come under sharp
criticism after it rejected some key candidates of the coalition
of the leftists and the moderates in the mid-term Majlis elections
in March.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months, supporters of the coalition have
repeatedly demanded the divestment of the council's screening
right in order that impartial elections be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
