<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls for Resumption of Cyprus Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. State Department special
coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller Wednesday called for a
resumption of the peace talks on the protracted Cyprus problem,
Turkey's official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
and State Minister Sukru Sina Gurel, Miller said that peace talks
would be effective ways to ease the tension prevailing in the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island, in the wake of an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is keeping more than 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to
protect the Turkish Cypriot minorities.
</P>
<P>
Miller urged the four parties related to the Cyprus issue -
Greece, Greek Cypriots, Turkey and Turkish Cypriots - to make
efforts in finding a framework of dialog aimed at bridging the gap
in key issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy arrived here Tuesday on a mission to help ward
off a possible confrontation between Turkey and Greece, both
members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, over Cyprus'
planned deployment of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, Cyprus signed a deal with Russia to buy the
missiles, which will be delivered in November.
</P>
<P>
The missile plan has prompted strong opposition from Turkey and
Turkish Cypriots. Ankara has vowed to take all necessary measures
to prevent the missile deployment.
</P>
<P>
Referring to speculation that the U.S. is pressing Turkey to
accept a no-fly zone over Cyprus, Miller said that he himself is
not aware of such a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
"I am not aware of any proposals of a moratorium. Looking at my
hands, do you see any proposals?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece and the Cypriot government dominated by the Greek
Cypriots have expressed support for a plan to create a no-fly zone
over Cyprus to ease tensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
