<HEADLINE> Hard Currency Control to Be Eased in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Finance Minister
Sufian Ahmed announced Wednesday that a mechanism to minimize
hard currency control will soon be put in force with a view to
bolstering the country's export.
</P>
<P>
Sufian told the official Ethiopian News Agency that while the
hard currency control is relaxed in the current 1998/99 fiscal
year, the country's export will be prop up, leading to the
increase in the foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
He said the liberalization will avoid unnecessary procedures
exporters had to pass through and make smooth export activities.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks will take over the work of hard currency
control from the National Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that an institution watching export promotion
activities and facilitating the expansion of Ethiopia's foreign
market will soon be set up.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia introduced foreign currency auction system in 1993.
In July, 1996, the government announced to lift some restrictions
on hard currency control, including merchants allowed to deposit
10 percent of the foreign curtrency they earn in their private
accounts and Ethiopiansloweo buy restricted mount of foreign
currency for the purpose of education, medication and
traveling abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
