<HEADLINE> Angola to Vie for Inter-Africa Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Angola proposed Wednesday to vie
for the secretary-general of Inter-Africa Coffee Organization
(OIAC), bringing the total candidates for the post to six.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan candidate is Josefa Sacko, an engineer and
counselor in the state secretariat for coffee. She will be the
first woman candidate in Africa for the post, the Angola News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sacko promised that if she is elected, she will make the
organization more vigorous.
</P>
<P>
Africa is one of the main coffee producing areas in the world,
she said, adding with a suggestion that the organization put
forth a new plan to increase productivity and improve the quality
of African coffee.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old Sacko has obtained a bachelor degree in
agriculture in Nigeria. However, she admitted that the post is a
mere political one, which has nothing to do with production.
</P>
<P>
The other five candidates are from Cameroon, Gabon, Nigeria
and the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the election of OIAC chief will be held in
September in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire where the headquarters of the
Organization is based.
</P>
<P>
The OIAC was founded in 1960 in Antananarivo, capital of
Madagascar. It consists Kenya, Uganda, DRC, Cote d'Ivoire, Gabon,
Madagascar, Benin and Angola.
</P>
<P>
Angola used to be a major coffee producer, the world's third
in terms of production. However, due to decades of civil war,
its current production can hardly meet domestic needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
