<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Self-Sufficient With Food: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is now self-sufficient
with food although some people are still suffering from hunger
and malnutrition, an agricultural official told Xinhua Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Joseph K. Mukiibi, the Director-General of the National
Agricultural Research Organization, said maize, millet, matoke,
rice are staple food for Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
Rice production has been on the rise in recent years, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Although the total amount of food the country produces is
sufficient for its population, the imbalanced distribution
results in famine and malnutrition in some places, the official
admitted.
</P>
<P>
Lack of storage facilities and food processing factories as
well as poor transport conditions are mainly responsible for the
imbalanced distribution of food.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Ugandans eat less meat, not only because
the price of meat is very high but also because they just do not
have cattle, sheep or pigs for meat.
</P>
<P>
Cattle in Uganda are considered as property. The more cattle
one possesses, the higher social status he enjoys. So cattle are
kept as an indicator of wealth and in some parts of the country
serve as dowry for a bride. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Canada's Supreme Court to Revive Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Canada is to
release its historic ruling Thursday on whether it would be legal
for Quebec to unilaterally secede from Canada.
</P>
<P>
The ruling is expected to revive the explosive debate and the
possibility that Quebec's pro-independence Parti Quebecois
government will call an election later this fall.
</P>
<P>
The case was brought by Canada's federal government, which
asked the top court for a legal opinion on three questions: Can
Quebec legally declare unilateral independence under domestic law?
Can it be done under international law? And, if there is a
conflict, which law rules?
</P>
<P>
Putting the case to the court was part of Ottawa' get-tough
approach toward separatists in the French-speaking province, which
voted almost itself out of Canada in a 1995 referendum on
independence.
</P>
<P>
The Quebec government has been vehemently opposed to the court
case and has refused to participate, forcing the court to appoint
a Quebec lawyer to argue the sovereigntist side.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard has criticized Ottawa and the
Supreme Court for interfering with Quebeckers' right to decide
whether to remain in Canada.
</P>
<P>
"This is a unilateral move by the federal government," he said
days before the ruling. "It's not up to the Supreme Court to
decide or limit in any way whatsoever the right of the Quebec
people to choose their future."
</P>
<P>
Most analysts here expect the federally-appointed nine judges
of the top court to rule in Ottawa's favor, even if they had to
nuance their words to try to deny ammunition to the separatists.
</P>
<P>
When the decision is released Thursday, politicians in Ottawa
and Quebec City will be poised to simplify and interpret,
celebrate, denounce or dismiss the judgement, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"In the short term, it could mean a resurgence of nationalist
excitement and a provincial election; it could be the platform for
an election in Quebec," noted David Cameron, political scientist
at the University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Premier Bouchard postponed a planned economic tour
of Latin America that was scheduled for November. It is seen as a
sure sign that a Quebec election may be in the making.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
