<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Japan to Do More to Open Photo Film Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday urged Japan to do more to open its photo market as a
way to solve the long-standing issue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Our report clearly points to the need for more aggressive
action by the Japanese government to ensure that all market access
barriers and practices that unreasonably restrict competition in
this sector are eliminated," said U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky in a statement accompanying the release of a
report by the U.S. Trade Representative Office and the U.S.
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to press Japan through formal and informal
means to reform its archaic distribution structure and address
practices that unreasonably restrain trade," she added.
</P>
<P>
The United States began monitoring Japan's photo film market
last February after it lost a landmark case in the World Trade
Organization -- the first case it brought and lost at the world
trade body. It was seen as a major setback for U.S. efforts to
open up the Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
After the loss of the case, the United States established the
Monitoring and Enforcement Committee, co-chaired by the U.S.
Trade Representative Office and the Commerce Department, to
review implementation of formal representations made by Japan to
a WTO panel regarding its efforts to ensure the openess of its
market to imports of film. And the U.S. inspection panel made
its first report on the photo film issue.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the availability of foreign photo film
declined slightly in traditional photo speciality stores, which
represents about half of Japan's film market by sales volume,
and competition in that segment of the market continues to be
less robust.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
