<HEADLINE> Uganda Removes Water Hyacinth With Mechanical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has been mainly using
mechanical means to remove water hyacinth in Lake Victoria as a
protection measure to the environment, an agricultural expert
told Xinhua in Entebbe, south Uganda, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Mukiibi, an official with the Ministry of Agriculture
based in Entebbe, 45 kms south of capital city Kampala, said Uganda
has compared biological and chemical ways with mechanical ways of
removing the water weed which covers large stretches of the lake
surface.
</P>
<P>
Four machines are being used on the lake surface near Jinja,
some 80 kms east of Kampala and near the capital, he added, with
each machine dragging out some 150 tons of hyacinth every day.
</P>
<P>
Some other methods have been tried, he said. Small insects are
introduced to eat the water weed, but the progress is very slow.
</P>
<P>
There are reportedly some 4,000 hectares of water surface and
70 percent of Uganda's lake shore covered with this weed. It
affects transport across the lake, fishing activities and power
generation.
</P>
<P>
The weed was allegedly flown into River Nile, causing flooding
of Lake Kyoga north of Kampala which displaced 15,000 people in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian experts have been invited to remove the blockage in
the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
