<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Suggests Unity Government in Guinea Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has suggested the establishment of a
unity government in Guinea Bissau as a way to solve the country's
political crisis, a report reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Andriene Diop, the spokeswoman for the
ECOWAS, as saying in Banjul, capital of Gambia, that the peace
plan was put to both sides of the conflict in Guinea Bissau
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Diop said the ECOWAS suggested parliamentary elections in
February 1999, with a national unity government until then.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested sending 100 ECOWAS observers to monitor the
ceasefire agreed on July 26.
</P>
<P>
An ECOWAS mediation delegation held separate meeting with the
government of President Joao Bernado Vieira and the rebels led by
dismissed Chief of Defense Staff, Ansumane Mane Monday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been engaged in fierce fightings in several
parts of the country since early June before a ceasefire was
agreed on July 26.
</P>
<P>
The two parties are expected to hold a face-to-face talk
Wednesday in Cape Verde, under the auspices of the Community of
Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPLP), the report said, adding
that it is their first direct contact since the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"It is positive that they have not decided to come here
because there cannot be dialog without the people (involved)
being present," Cape Verde Foreign Minister Jose Luis de Jesus
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, who is in Cape Verde,
said the CPLP and the ECOWAS had agreed to meet within the next
few days to resolve outstanding problems that could impede moves
toward peace in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, ECOWAS has been asked to steer clear of the crisis in
Guinea Bissau, but it refused on the ground that Guinea Bissau is
a member of the sub-regional body.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had initially rejected any mediation by ECOWAS
because two of its members, Guinea and Senegal, were supporting
President Vieira militarily.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, ECOWAS's peace plan envisages scaling
down the number of troops from the two countries. Enitem

