<HEADLINE> Gingrich Says Let Legal Process Work in Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- America should move past the
titillating talk about President Bill Clinton's relationship with
Monica Lewinsky and let the legal process do its job, Speaker Newt
Gingrich of the House of Representatives said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The core of this civilization is the rule of law," Gingrich
told the Gwinnett County Chamber of Commerce in Georgia. "We have
an absolute obligation to ensure the rule of law. I have no
interest in personal scandals."
</P>
<P>
"No one is above the law," The Associated Press quoted Gingrich
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Georgia Republican said he will continue to wait for the
report that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is expected to
submit to Congress. And he said Congress -- led by the Judiciary
Committee and its chairman, Republican Representative Henry Hyde
-- will review the report in a "dispassionate manner."
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we should go an inch beyond our constitutional
duties, and I don't think we should go an inch less than our
constitutional duties," the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
Congress has "lots to do without all of us being totally
mesmerized," he said, adding that that advice applies to the media
as well.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich suggested they devote 15 minutes of every half hour to
"Monica-less time."
</P>
<P>
"It would make us a much healthier country if the news media
took a pretty big break and just said, `Let's focus on other
things for a while and let Judge Starr continue his job,'"
Gingrich said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
