<HEADLINE> Ireland Announces "Draconian" Measures to Omagh Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
announced "extremely draconion" measures on Wednesday to crack
down on terrorism in the wake of the Omagh bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
"These measures are extremely draconian, but I am not prepared
to take the chance of anything else and these measures have to be
implemented quickly," Ahern was quoted as saying in Dublin after a
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ahern said Ireland's anti-terrorism laws would restrict the
right to silence of guerrilla suspects and extend the maximum
detention period from 48 to 96 hours before being charged.
</P>
<P>
The new measures were intended to bring to justice the
guerrillas responsible for the Omagh blast last Saturday which
killed 28 people and wounded more than 200.
</P>
<P>
The Irish parliament will be recalled in two weeks time to push
through the new security legislation, Ahern told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The "Real IRA", which has admitted responsibility for the Omagh
attack, declared a ceasefire on Wednesday after Ahern on Tuesday
gave paramilitary groups 24 hours to declare ceasefires or face
the wrath of his government.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the suspension of military violence, both
Britain and Ireland said the truce would make no difference to
their plans to hunt down on the bombers.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to leave no stone unturned to hunt the men
that did this," Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said.
</P>
</TEXT>
