<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Urged to Import More Raw Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine food processors and
exporters have asked the government for a special allocation of
20,000 to 30,000 metric tons (MT) raw sugar that could be imported
at zero to 10 percent tariff.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Food Processors and Exporters Organization Inc
(Philfoodex) President Jesus Tanchanco told reporters Thursday
that the volume is separate from the 200,000 MT raw sugar imports
the government hopes to bring in in August and next month.
</P>
<P>
Tanchanco said the sector is also asking for at least zero
percent tariff for proposed volume instead of 65 percent imposed
on minimum access volume (MAV) plus.
</P>
<P>
Low tariff, he said, is expected to provide due advantage for
Philippine sugar-based products as against competitors including
Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Our members have already slowed down their production,"
Tanchanco said. "Right now, many of them could not get sugar in
the local market."
</P>
<P>
He said the group thus hopes the government could give them the
allocation initially at 10,000 MT as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The sector has not yet received any favorable response to the
request. Concerned agencies including the Sugar Regulatory
Administration are currently studying the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Philfoodex comprises the country's 200 biggest food processors
and exporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
