<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Scale Down Use of Dollar in ASEAN Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia expects to use its
currency more widely for trade with its ASEAN partners through
signing bilateral payment agreements (BPA) with them to reduce the
dependence on the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry Deputy Secretary-General (Policy) Abdul Aziz
Mohd Yaacob said Thursday that Malaysia, which has already signed
the BPAs with the Philippines, Vietnam and Laos in the wake of the
regional economic crisis, is negotiating with Thailand to sign a
similar agreement.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Myanmar have also indicated their interest and it
is expected that the other ASEAN countries would follow suit,
Abdul Aziz said at a seminar in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to use regional currencies in intra-ASEAN trade
was made by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and was well
received by ASEAN leaders at their second informal summit held in
Kuala Lumpur last December.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN is Malaysia's largest trading partner with volume
increasing from 29.33 billion U.S. dollars in 1994 to 37.32
billion U.S. dollars in 1996 before declining to 27.46 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of Malaysia's trade settlements are conducted
using the U.S. dollar which has appreciated against many
currencies. Only about 15 percent of the trade are in the
Malaysian currency ringgit and 6.5 percent in the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a fair share of Malaysia's trade with Brunei,
Singapore and Thailand was settled using their respective
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all trade with Myanmar, Vietnam and Laos were settled in
the U.S. dollar which was also used for 97 percent of Malaysia's
exports to and 93 percent of its imports from the Philippines and
for 90 percent imports from and 77 percent exports to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Aziz said the use of ASEAN currencies will enhance trade
within the region because of the reduction in exchange rate
uncertainty and transaction costs as the values of the ASEAN
currencies relative to one another are more stable than in the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said the promotion of intra-ASEAN trade using local
currencies will be a strategic initiative in light of its expected
significant expansion with the creation of the ASEAN Free Trade
Area and the ASEAN Investment Area.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that with the growing acceptance of the BPA
mechanism within ASEAN, the bilateral arrangement can be expanded
into a multi-lateral arrangement.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huaneng Power Company's Net Profit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The net profit of the Huaneng
Power International, Inc., one of the largest independent power
producers in China, amounted to 801 million (RMB) Yuan (97 million
U.S. dollars) in the first half of this year, a top company
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This represents a 32.07 percent increase over the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Announcing Huaneng's interim results at a press conference
here, Wang Xiaosong, deputy general manager of the company, said
its net operating revenues for the first half of the year were
about 3,754 million (RMB) Yuan (453 million U.S. dollars).
Earnings per American Depository Share were 6 (RMB) Yuan, an
increase of 25 percent as compared to the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Huaneng, which listed its shares on the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange in January this year, has seven operating power plants
with a total power generation of 12.423 billion KWH during the
first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
This accounts for 45 percent of the total planned generation
for the whole year of 1998, and is also a 49.57 percent increase
over the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the company's four power projects in Dandong, Dalian,
Nantong and Fuzhou under construction are progressing well. The
investments are all within budget and the quality of construction
is satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Commissioning of Dalian Power Plant Phase 2 and Dandong Power
Plant has commenced on schedule, he added.
</P>
<P>
Wang also acknowledged that the company's results were
adversely affected by market and natural factors in the first half
of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
