<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Tightens Control on Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnam government has issued
a new decree on foreign exchange management, an official said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decree, signed by Prime Minister Phan Van Khai on August
17, introduces new stipulations for foreign exchange transactions,
trading and transfer of capital to and from Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The government issued the decree in order to improve Vietnam's
foreign exchange control system, to make the Vietnamese dong
convertible in foreign trading, to stimulate economic growth, and
to improve the balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
In the decree, the state bank of Vietnam will determine and
announce daily foreign exchange rates between the Vietnamese dong
and foreign currencies; the rates will be regulated on a
supply-demand basis.
</P>
<P>
The decree stipulates that the government shall exercise
uniform control of all foreign exchanges and foreign
exchange-related activities, which shall be conducted only through
the banking system or by individuals or organizations permitted to
do so.
</P>
<P>
The decree says that foreign investment capital in cash must be
deposited at banks currently operating in Vietnam and that
investors must register their capital contributions in foreign
currency at the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Capital in cash transferred abroad must be conducted through
accounts opened at local banks and registered at the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Investors must remit all their investment capital, profits and
legal income to Vietnam after their projects expire.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors can trade in stocks and other valuable papers
in accordance with foreign exchanges rules.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said the central bank will soon issue a circular
guiding the implementation of the decree, including a regulation
requiring those carrying 5,000 U.S.dollars or ten million
Vietnamese dong abroad must declare it at the border gates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
