<HEADLINE> HK New Airport's Cargo Handling To Be Fully Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
Ltd. (HACTL), the operator of SuperTerminal 1 at Hong Kong
International Airport, said Thursday that all HACTL's air cargo,
both inbound and outbound, will be handled at SuperTerminal 1 from
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
This move represents the successful completion some eight days
ahead of schedule of a four-phase air cargo recovery program, said
HACTL, the major air cargo operator at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The Special Administrative Region (SAR) government welcomed the
announcement. "We are pleased to learn that HACTL will resume all
cargo handling services at the new airport ahead of its schedule
of recovery program," said a government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"With full recovery of the air cargo operation at the new
airport, we are confident that Hong Kong will continue to be a
major air cargo center in the world," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
SuperTerminal 1, built at a cost of over 1 billion U.S.
dollars, is now handling 90 percent of HACTL's cargo, with the
remainder processed at Terminal 2 of Kai Tak, Hong Kong's old
airport.
</P>
<P>
"Since the recovery program began (on July 18), the measured
build up of operations at SuperTerminal 1 has progressed smoothly
and has enabled us to address and rectify teething problems in a
controlled manner," said Anthony Charter, HACTL's managing
director.
</P>
<P>
"It has indeed been unfortunate that SuperTerminal 1 was not
able fully to meet all customer needs from start up and we regret
the inconvenience caused," Charter said.
</P>
<P>
With the early completion of the recovery program,
SuperTerminal 1 will be well prepared for the start of Hong Kong's
peak period for cargo handling which normally begins in September
and lasts for about four months, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
