<HEADLINE> People in North China Battle Surging Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- People in north China's
Heilongjiang and Jilin provinces and Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region are sparing no effort to fight the disastrous floods.
</P>
<P>
In northernmost Heilongjiang Province, Xu Youfang, secretary of
the provincial committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
and provincial governor Tian Fengshan have been staying at
dangerous sections of the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers for days to
help solve problems of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
The 26-km-long riverbank in Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang,
looks like a battlefield. Officers and men of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) have built a 300-m-long second defense
barrier in the city proper and piled up sandbags on the Songhua
embankment to raise its height.
</P>
<P>
A tricycle team made up of farmers travelled 100 km every day
to transport stone and sandbags to the river embankment.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials at provincial and bureau levels in Jilin
Province rushed to dangerous sections to direct flood-fighting
when the crest reached there.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dejiang, secretary of the Jilin CPC Provincial Committee,
went to Zhenlai, the worst-hit area, to arrange evacuation of
local residents and helped them with foodstuffs, living conditions
and drinking water.
</P>
<P>
The city of Baicheng has aroused 4 million people to reinforce
river dikes and repair dangerous sections. Local railway
departments formed shock repair teams to maintain normal rail
traffic.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Inner Mongolia have visited flood-hit areas to
direct the flood fight, to study the flood situation, to arrange
relief materials and to visit flood victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
