<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Moves to Placate Investors, Depositors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia's central bank on
Thursday assured nationals that their deposits in banks would be
fully guaranteed, a fresh effort to soothe the panicked citizens
rushing to dump their devalued rubles in exchange for hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
"The Central Bank is urging Russian citizens not to convert
their deposits in haste and not to withdraw their money from
banks," Sergei Dubinin, chairman of the Central Bank of Russia,
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The ruble's official exchange rate shot to 6.996 to the
U.S. dollar Thursday, three days after the government and the
central bank raised the ceiling of the exchange corridor of the
national currency from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dubinin also urged the country's commercial banks to create a
system of mutual guarantees on deposits, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said commercial banks should conclude agreements with
Sberbank (Savings Bank of the Russian Federation) assuring that
every private investor has the right to state-guaranteed safety of
deposits pending a law guaranteeing the safety of deposits.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, as Sberbank's main shareholder, has already
issued relevant instructions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko is scheduled to
meet with a group of foreign investors later Thursday to address
their concerns over Russia's obligations to international loans.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko will brief the investors on the government's measures
for stabilizing the Russian financial market, the government
information department said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's top negotiator with international lending agencies
Anatoly Chubais, Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Fyodorov, and Dubinin are likely to take part in
the meeting, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The government skipped a self-imposed deadline Wednesday to
announce how it intended to restructure the domestic debt market.
Western bankers greeted the silence with relief, saying Russia
could use the extra time to hear their concerns and suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko on Thursday continued to defend the government moves
on restructuring the state debt and a broader corridor for the
ruble, a euphemism for ruble devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The measures, although painful and unpleasant, are necessary to
prevent the general situation from sliding out of control, he told
a government meeting.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the core reason for the country's
economic chaos came from inside the country, although the Asian
financial crisis and battered world oil prices also hit the
Russian economy hard.
</P>
<P>
"No outside factors could have affected so negatively our
economy if we had not had our own domestic problems," Kiriyenko
said.
</P>
<P>
He said if the decision on restructuring the state debt had not
been taken, the government would have to service it, sacrificing
wages of miners, teachers, medical workers and the servicemen in
the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The country's wage arrears reached 75.84 billion rubles (10.85
billion dollars) on August 1 in 10 basic industries, up 6.5
percent from the beginning of July, the State Statistics Committee
said Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Eight Omagh Victims Laid to Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- People in Omagh, a Northern
Ireland market town which had a car bomb blast last weekend,
buried the last eight victims on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Omagh said the funerals were held in and around
the town, 80 km west of Belfast, during the day.
</P>
<P>
The blast claimed 28 lives, including three small boys from an
Irish Republic seaside town, a baby, a mother and a grandmother
from one family, and two visiting Spaniards.
</P>
<P>
Two funeral ceremonies were held in the center of Omagh on
Thursday just meters from the courthouse that warning messages had
led police to believe was the target for bombers from the
so-called Real IRA.
</P>
<P>
The funeral for Debra-Anne Cartwright, 20, a Protestant who
worked in a beauty salon in the town center, was held at St
Columba's Church.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of mourners were attending ceremonies in and around
the town. Northern Ireland First Minister David Trmible was among
mourners at the Holy Trinity Church in Lislimnaghan.
</P>
<P>
Reports said 76 of the more than 200 people injured when the
bomb exploded are still in hospital. 
