<HEADLINE> Canada's Top Court Rules on Quebec Separation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Canada ruled
out Thursday any chance for French-speaking province of Quebec to
unilaterally claim independence from the country.
</P>
<P>
In its historic ruling on the Quebec issue, the top court said
that the province can not separate from Canada under the
Constitution of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Nor can Quebec separate from the country under international
law, the nine-member court ruled.
</P>
<P>
But the court also noted that if a clear majority of Quebecers
vote to get out of Canada, then the federal government and the
rest of provinces would have the obligation to negotiate with
Quebec and amend the constitution so that Quebec could leave.
</P>
<P>
The government of Quebec led by Premier Lucien Bouchard, said
earlier that it would not accept the court's ruling and it
boycotted court hearings on the matter earlier this year. 
</P>
