<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Primer on Canada's Supreme Court References </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Canada is to
hand down its ruling on the legality of a unilateral separation by
Quebec Thursday morning. The following are some questions and
answers about the issue.
</P>
<P>
What's a reference?
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has used its reference power to ask the
court to make the ruling on the Quebec issue.
</P>
<P>
A reference is a process which allows the government to ask the
court for advice on legal or factual questions having to do with
interpreting the constitution, laws or the powers of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Is it unusual?
</P>
<P>
There have been a total of 74 references by the federal government
since the first one in 1892. In 1981, for example, the top court was
asked to decided whether Ottawa could patriate the constitution without the
consent of all the provinces.
</P>
<P>
But internationally, it is an unusual power. The high courts of
Australia and the United States, for example, can't issue advisory opinions.
</P>
<P>
What questions has the court been asked?
</P>
<P>
1. Under Canada's constitution, can Quebec unilaterally separate
from the rest of the country?
</P>
<P>
2. Under international law, can Quebec secede ?
</P>
<P>
3. If Canadian and international law conflict, which prevails?
</P>
<P>
Is the court's judgement binding?
</P>
<P>
No. The court issues an advisory opinion. Since it's from the
highest court it has always been treated as binding, but it can be
disregarded by the government.
</P>
<P>
Why did the Canadian government ask the court of its opinion?
</P>
<P>
The reference is part of the government's get-tough approach to
Quebec separation. It hopes to set out ground rules for sucession.
But Quebec has refused to take part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0082 </DOCNO>
