<HEADLINE> Roundup: All Out Efforts to Combat Raging Floods in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- While the sixth flood crest
flowed through the middle reaches of the Yangtze river today, the
flooding situation on the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers caused
concern.
</P>
<P>
A new flood crest on the Songhua river is pressing toward
Harbin, a major industrial city and capital of Heilongjiang
Province. A large numbers of soldiers and civilians are pledging
their lives to safeguard the city.
</P>
<P>
At 2 p.m. today, the water level at Harbin had risen to 120.77
meters, 0.72 meters more than the record high, with a flow of
17,300 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Tonight the sixth Yangtze flood crest is expected to pass
Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province. At the same
time, the city will also be hit by another flood crest on the
Hanjiang River. Experts believe this is a crucial moment for the
city.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin has phoned Wen Jiabao, vice-premier of
the State Council and head of the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters, and Xu Youfang, secretary of Heilongjiang
Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC),
several times to inquire about detailed anti-flood measures and to
issue a series of important directives.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called on all army and civilian flood-fighters along the
Nenjiang and Songhua rivers to spare no effort to protect major
cities, the Daqing Oil Field and the lives of local people.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji this morning phoned Wang Maolin, secretary
of the Hunan Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party,
demanding continuous and concentrated efforts to fight the Yangtze
floods.
</P>
<P>
Wen Jiabao inspected Harbin and Dorbod Autonomous County of
Mongolian ethnic group in Heilongjiang Province, Zhenlai County in
Jilin Province and Horqin Left Wing Middle Banner in the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region Wednesday and today.
</P>
<P>
At present, 75,000 PLA soldiers and armed police are fighting
the floods on the front line in northeast China, a major grain
producer for the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters today
sent more materials to flood-ravaged areas along the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze and the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers
in the northeast. By Wednesday, the headquarters had sent 200
million yuan worth of goods to the areas.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and foreign donations sent to the Ministry of Civil
Affairs and its sub-departments across the country have to date
totalled more than 1.06 billion yuan (130 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry has allocated relief materials worth 131 million
yuan to the flooded areas, a Ministry official said today.
</P>
<P>
China Central Television hosted an evening show on Sunday which
raised more than 600 million yuan (75 million U.S. dollars) in
donations for the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has also pledged that every penny
of the funds raised will be used for the country's flood victims,
whose total number exceeds 240 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
