<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Remains Low in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide
unemployment rate still remains low, the Labor Department said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic crisis helped slow the nation's economic
growth from a 5.5 percent annual rate during the first three
months of this year to 1.4 percent during the second quarter
period. However, jobs remain plentiful and the unemployment rate
in July, at 4.5 percent, remained near a 28-year low.
</P>
<P>
The number of first-time claims for unemployment benefits fell
by 2,000 to a seasonally adjusted 303,000 last week, according to
the department. The figure is well below the 394,000 reached for
two consecutive weeks in late June and early July, when
unemployment was nudged higher by the nearly-two-month General
Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
A four-week average of claims fell to 303,000, down from
307,000 for the period ending one week earlier. It was the lowest
level in a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
