<HEADLINE> Canadian to Head Ad Hoc Committee on Fissile Material Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Canada's ambassador to the
Conference on Disarmament (CD) Mark Moher was named here Thursday
as chairman of a newly-established ad hoc committee on talks to
ban production of bomb-level fissile material.
</P>
<P>
After his appointment by consensus within the CD, Moher pledged
to be neutral as chairman of the negotiations to be re-launched
after having been stalled since 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Canada, as chairman of the committee, undertakes and commits
itself to behave as a chairman should, i.e. in a neutral way. The
Canadian chair will do its best to move the work of the committee
forward but to do so in a way sensitive to member states of the
conference," Moher said.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, the 61-member CD decided to establish the ad hoc
committee on the prohibition of production of fissile material for
nuclear purposes.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the committee is to negotiate a
non-discriminatory, multilateral and internationally and
effectively verifiable treaty banning the production of fissile
material for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices,
said a statement issued by the 61-member disarmament conference.
</P>
<P>
The ad hoc committee shall present a report to the Conference
on Disarmament on the progress of its efforts to launch fresh
talks on a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty (FMCT) before the
conclusion of the 1998 session of CD on September 9. 
</P>
