<HEADLINE> No Military Response to Congo (K) Crisis: Nzo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo Thursday repeated South Africa's position
that there should be no military intervention in the present
crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"In fact, there can be no military solution to this problem,"
Nzo told the National Assembly in Cape Town. "A solution that we
are convinced will be meaningful will be one decided upon by the
Congolese people themselves."
</P>
<P>
His speech was televised live on South African national
television, the SABC.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said South Africa's ultimate goal is to
help bring about a broad-based political order in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the present conflict in the country was the
failure to establish such an order, said Nzo.
</P>
<P>
He said that the best way to resolve the problem is to seek a
cease-fire in the country and then let the DRC people decide
their own future by a general election.
</P>
<P>
"It was clear to us that what needed to be done in this
situation was to work for a situation of a cease-fire so as to
enable the Congolese in a calm atmosphere to sit around a table
and to determine the future of their country, a solution which
would entail, among other things, the establishment of a
broad-based interim government to prepare for eventual elections
later, in other words, for the Congolese people to be given an
opportunity to decide their own future."
</P>
<P>
"I must now indicate that what we are busily engaged in at
this moment is to precisely reach that position whereby a
cease-fire is declared and the beginnings of a discussion by the
Congolese people themselves for the settlement of their problem
will take place," said Nzo.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his mission to Rwanda and Uganda Tuesday
and Wednesday, he warned the leaders of the two countries that
the crisis would not end even after Kinshasa has been taken by
rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
"During the course of our discussions with the leadership of
both Rwanda and Uganda, we indicated that this crisis will by no
means end after Kinshasa has been taken," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a crisis that is likely to continue to bedevil the
region for a very long time," the South African minister added.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda were accused by DRC President Laurent Kabila
of being behind the rebel forces in his country, but both
countries denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Certain southern African countries led by Zimbabwe are in
favor of military assistance to Kabila to help quell the revolt.
</P>
</TEXT>
