<HEADLINE> IOC to Strengthen Fight against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) executive committee on Thursday charged four
special task forces with the job to fight against drugs in sport
in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The four groups have until February next year to come up with
a solution which will then be presented to a special two-day
international world conference on sports doping to be held in
Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Following are the four areas to be covered:
</P>
<P>
1. Protection of athletes.
</P>
<P>
2. The political and legal position, the definition of doping
and government co-operation.
</P>
<P>
3. Ethics and prevention.
</P>
<P>
4. The financial stakes and the relationship between doping
and money. How to fight against doping.
</P>
<P>
Revealing the four target areas, IOC director general Francois
Carrard said the executive committee was determined to do
everything possible to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The IOC hopes Thursday's decision will be the first step in
revolutionizing how doping cheats in sport are caught and
punished.
</P>
<P>
However, how to define what doping is will be the most
important problem the IOC task forces is facing.
</P>
<P>
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch complained there were too
long list on substances and that he saw nothing wrong with
performance-enhancing drugs if there was no health risk.
</P>
<P>
The task force will have to find a compromise between the two
opposite views. 
</P>
</TEXT>
