<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Moves to Tighten Grip on Banking Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia has passed an
amendment to tighten the legal grip on banking activities.
</P>
<P>
The amendment to the banking law was approved Thursday by the
Great Hural, or the parliament. The amendment will target
liability dodgers and those who abuse power for personal gain.
</P>
<P>
Those persons who deliberately evade their debt payment
responsibility and abuse power to serve their personal interest
will be subject to imprisonment for up to five years and the
confiscation of their illegal gains.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendment, commercial banks could be fined 10 million
tugriks (118,000 U.S. dollars) if they fail to present their final
reports and balance sheets to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, those in charge could be fined 250,000
tugriks (2,900 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has decided to intensify control of the banking system
since banks in the inland Asian country are plagued by bad debts.
</P>
<P>
An aborted merger of a state bank with a private counterpart in
May led to the fall of the former cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Draws Lessons From Asian Financial Crisis  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A major lesson China's financial
leaders have learned from the still lingering Asian crisis is that
efforts must be made to prevent economic bubbles during periods of
rapid expansion.
</P>
<P>
During periods of rapid economic growth, both domestic and
overseas investment should be directed to sustainable growth
projects to prevent excessive increases in stock and real estate
prices, said Liu Mingkang, vice-governor of the People's Bank of
China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today to participants of a seminar on the Asian
financial crisis and the development of financial markets on the
Chinese mainland and Hong Kong, Liu also said that currency
convertibility under the capital account must be achieved
gradually.
</P>
<P>
A stable and efficient domestic banking system, a balanced
macro economy and a mature domestic capital market are three
prerequites for capital-account convertibility, he said.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of a currency, meanwhile, should be decided
in accordance with the soundness of the balance of international
payments as well as that of the macro economy, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"Only when the exchange rate is rightfully set, can adequate
foreign exchange reserves be meaningful as a stabilizer," he said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should also be made to control the expansion of the
size of foreign debt to keep the debt-service ratio below the
international warning level, Liu said, adding that the foreign
debt structure must also be kept reasonable.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the central bank must enhance
supervision over the banking sector to ensure that commercial
banks do operate according to accepted international standards.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, administrative intervention in banking
business must be cut to the minimum level while openness must be
increased in making financial policies.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that it is common knowledge that China has contributed
greatly to regional economic stability during the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"China's policy of maintaining the yuan's exchange rate has
eased the export pressure of crisis-hit countries and helped to
avoid competitive, hostile currency devaluations in the region,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Flood-Fighters Prepare for Arrival of Sixth Flood Crest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 280,000 army and
civilian flood-fighters are working day and night on the
465-kilometer-long embankment of the Yangtze River in Wuhan to
prepare for the arrival of the sixth flood crest.
</P>
<P>
The water level in Wuhan remained at 29.43 meters for 23 hours
ending at 8 p.m. today. The flow rate reached 73,200 cubic meters
per second.
</P>
<P>
The sustained high water level was fed by water pouring down
from the upper reaches of the Yangtze, which joined floodwaters
from the Hanjiang, Yuanshui and Lishui rivers, said an official
from the Yangtze Water Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
When the flood crest passes Wuhan on Friday, the water level is
expected to reach 29.47 meters, according to the State Flood
Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
To date, the river embankments in Wuhan have been soaked in
water above the record level of 29 meters for more than 20
days. Thunderstorms with gale-force winds were pouring down on the
city at 8 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
A rally for flood-fighters was held this morning on the
embankment of the Yangtze amid roaring shouts of slogans and vows
to overcome the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Wuhan flood control headquarters issued its ninth order
today, calling on all the people in the city to be on high alert
and prepare to pay any price to ensure the city's safety.
</P>
<P>
At present, huge amounts of sandbags, stones and other
necessary materials are being shipped to key sections of the
embankments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Draws Lessons From Asian Financial Crisis  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China also has been largely successful in taking measures to
minimize the negative impact of the crisis, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the crisis has had a direct impact on Chinese exports
and the potential to inhibit China's effort to raise funds
overseas and on foreign direct investment in China, he admitted.
</P>
<P>
China's export growth has slowed since January, with total
exports rising 7.6 percent year-on-year to 87 billion U.S. dollars
for the first half of this year, official figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
In a sharp contrast to massive drops in overseas capital inflow
into Asia, China still registered 20.5 billion U.S. dollars in
overseas direct investment in the first six months of this year,
which is almost the same as for the same period last year, Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
Newly pledged overseas investment in China reached 24.2 billion
yuan in the January-June period, up 5.5 percent from a year ago,
as against a downward trend in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
"Massive reductions in investment from Asia have been offset by
significant increases in investment from Europe and America," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
While actively drawing lessons from the Asian financial crisis,
China is also resolutely pushing ahead financial reforms to
prevent and ward off financial risks, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has posed a rigorous test for the
sustained and stable development of the Chinese economy, Liu
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
"However, the active fiscal and administrative policies and the
monetary policy of appropriately increasing money supply will, to
a great extent, offset the negative impact from without," he said.
</P>
<P>
So long as China sticks to its economic restructuring and the
policies of reform and opening to the outside world, it still can
realize relatively rapid economic growth, Liu said, and this
itself is a great contribution to the economy of the region and
that of the whole world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
