<HEADLINE> Yorke on His Way to Man United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Aston Villa accepted a 12
million pounds (19.50 million U.S. dollars) offer by Manchester
United for their Trinidad and Tobago striker Dwight Yorke on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports today, Yorke was already in the
Manchester United club to discuss personal terms with United
manager Alex Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
The deal was expected to be completed before Thursday's 2200
GMT European transfer deadline which will enable Yorke to play
for United in the Champions' League this season.
</P>
<P>
If it goes through, the transfer will end weeks of speculation
in the media and negotiation between the clubs.
</P>
<P>
United initially offered around 8m for the 26-year-old Yorke,
but Villa valued him at 16m and it looked as though no deal could
be reached, even after the bid was increased to 10m.
</P>
<P>
Yorke has said he is keen to make the move as he wants to play
at the highest level in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United are in the Champions' League while Aston
Villa are only in the UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
Just three days ago, Yorke said: "I want to go to Manchester
United. The Champions' League deadline is on Thursday and I want
to be there by then."
</P>
<P>
Villa chairman Doug Ellis tried to placate Yorke by arguing
that his team would soon compete at United's level, but he failed
to convince his star. 
</P>
</TEXT>
