<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Takes Vehicle Trade Dispute with Canada to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Thursday that it is taking Canada to the World Trade Organization
(WTO) over automobile trade discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union (EU), is requesting formal consultation with the WTO to end
the Canadian policy of subsidizing local automobile companies.
</P>
<P>
The commission argued that the Canadian policy breaks WTO rules
and distorts international trade practices by giving some
companies an unfair advantage over their European competitors.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government, commission officials said, grants
selected companies the right to import both automobile components
and finished vehicles duty-free, provided they use a minimum
portion of Canadian components and their production in Canada
represents a designated percentage of sales in the country.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of required local components and the mandatory
production-to-sales ratio, however, varies from company to company.
</P>
<P>
Canada now levies a 6.7-percent tariff on vehicles and a
6-percent tariff on automobile components imported from the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
EU exports of automobile products to the North American country
increased to 1,026 million ECU (1,128 million U.S. dollars) in
1997, from 775 million ECU (852.5 million dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials quoted official Canadian sources as saying
that more than 16 percent of the total imports of vehicles from
the EU were duty-free in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
