<HEADLINE> Seoul Stock Prices Up Over Stabilized Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Seoul Share prices rose 4.87
percent Thursday as the Japanese yen stabilized and foreign
investors registered a rare net selling in the market.
</P>
<P>
The composite stock price index surged 14.69 points to close
the day at 316.59. Advancing issues outnumbered decliners at 638
against 155, with 77 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Turnover rose to 91.46 million shares worth 509.99 billion won
(about 394.12 million U.S. dollars) changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors launched a rare buying spree in the market,
concentrating on key blue-chips and under-valued large cap
issues. They marked a net purchase figure of 14 billion won, while
retail investors outdid their foreign counterparts to mark net
purchases of 26.9 billion won.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, institutional investors remained bearish, marking
net selling figures of a whopping 45.1 billion won.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean won Thursday strengthened to 1,294 against the
U.S. dollar from the previous day's closing of 1,305 won. But the
benchmark three-year corporate bond yield remained unchanged at
13.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
