<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Online Advertising to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Global spending for online
advertising will hit 15 billion U.S. dollars in 2003, an American
technology research firm said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Forrester Research, Inc. based its estimation on the steady
growth in the world's online population and the arrival of
mainstream advertisers.
</P>
<P>
The company said that spending for online advertising will
continue to be dominated by the United States, with Internet
advertisements growing from 1.3 billion dollars in 1998 to 10.5
billion dollars in 2003.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. share of the worldwide market will decline from 87
percent in 1998 to 70 percent in 2003, Forrester said, adding that
the global online advertisement spending was estimated at one
billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Outside the United States, advertisement spending will be led
by Europe, where the online market is expected to grow from 105
million dollars in 1998 to 2.8 billion dollars in 2003.
</P>
<P>
This spending, Forrester said, will be pushed by an
increasingly cohesive European market, a growing Internet
population, competition from U.S.-based companies and maturing
technologies.
</P>
<P>
Slowed by ongoing economic difficulties, Asian advertisement
spending will grow to 1.25 billion dollars in 2003. Dramatic
growth in Latin America will be masked by a small Internet
population and a low starting point for advertisement spending, it
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has arrived as an accepted advertising medium,"
Forrester's report said. "This is evidenced by the amounts that
will be spent for online advertisements during the next five
years, as well as by the arrival of large mainstream advertisers."
</P>
<P>
In addition to the growth in overall spending, Forrester
expected per capita spending for online advertisements in the
United States to bypass radio and magazine advertisements by 2003.
</P>
<P>
Internet advertisers will spend 25 dollars per person in 1998
-- double the amount spent in 1997. By 2003, this number will grow
to 104 dollars per person, roughly one-third of per capita
spending for television advertisements but slightly ahead of
magazine and radio spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
