<HEADLINE> Egypt's Shopping Festival Boosts Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's first month-long Shopping
and Tourism Festival, which ends Thursday, turned out to be
successful, giving a big stimulus to the country's tourism, the
Middle East News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The number of tourists was up from the same period last
year. Moreover, hotel occupancy rates were very high, even
unprecedented," said Tourism Minister Mamdouh El-Beltagui Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 174,000 foreigners and 112,000 Egyptian expatriates
flocked to Egypt during the festival, which made the number of
visitors to Egypt this summer far greater than the same period
last year despite a five-week-long heat wave.
</P>
<P>
The visitors mostly came to buy carpets, crystals and
chandeliers, which are among the wide-ranging merchandise sold at
up to 50 percent discount in the festival, the agency said,
quoting customs and banking officials.
</P>
<P>
During the festival started July 20 in Cairo and the Red Sea
resort of Hurghada, visitors can not only enjoy a maximum discount
of 50 percent in stores, but also in hotels and the EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the two cities, the average hotel
occupancy reached over 90 percent in the month.
</P>
<P>
The festival is part of Egypt's efforts to boost its tourism,
the second key foreign currency earner which suffered a grave
setback last year after the Luxor incident in southern Egypt, in
which 58 foreign tourists were killed by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a total of 4 million tourists, about 20
percent of them from other Arab states, visited Egypt last year,
bringing 3.8 billion dollars to the state treasury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
