<HEADLINE> Chinese President Plays Role in Flood Situation  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President and Party
General Secretary Jiang Zemin has concerned himself with the
anti-flood battle along the two major rivers in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Jiang placed two calls to Wen Jiabao, vice-premier
and head of the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters, to ask about the flood situation on the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers. Jiang also issued a series of important directives
to Wen.
</P>
<P>
He then called Xu Youfang, secretary of the Heilongjiang
Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), to
inquire about detailed anti-flood measures taken there.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday evening, the president made a third call to Wen
after the vice-premier had arrived in Harbin, capital of
Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called on all army and civilian flood-fighters along the
two rivers to spare no effort to protect major cities, the Daqing
Oilfield and the lives of local people.
</P>
<P>
Wen inspected Harbin and the Dorbod Autonomous County of ethnic
Mongolia group in Heilongjiang Province as well as Zhenlai County
in Jilin and Horqin Left Wing Middle Banner in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
He extended cordial regards to military and civilian
flood-fighters and flood victims on behalf of the CPC Central
Committee and the State Council as well as Jiang Zemin and Premier
Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
Wen also visited the third defense embankment on Wednesday,
which is under construction to protect the Daqing Oilfield. He
conveyed Jiang's message on flood-fighting and urged all people
present to unite as one to safeguard the Daqing Oilfield. In the
afternoon, he arrived at the embankments in Harbin and encouraged
people to exert themselves to the utmost to combat the
unprecedented flood crest.
</P>
