<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Medical Team to Perform Eye Surgeries in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A national medical team of 20
outstanding ophthalmologists will soon leave for Tibet to provide
free surgeries for about 1,000 blind cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
This will be the biggest rehabilitation service in the history
of the Tibet Autonomous Region, Health Minister Zhang Wenkang said
today at a ceremony to present a mission flag to team members.
</P>
<P>
One month of medical service will be given to farmers and
herdsmen in four areas of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Tibetans run much higher risks of cataract-related blindness
because of the high altitude and strong ultraviolet rays.
</P>
<P>
"The incidence of cataracts in Tibet is twice as high as in
other regions of China, and cataracts generally occur 10-to-15
years earlier," Zhang said, adding that the lack of medical
facilities and transportation problems make the situation even
worse.
</P>
<P>
Cataracts are the cause of blindness for more than four million
Chinese, almost half of the total number of blind people across
the country. Each year, about 400,000 new cases of blindness are
caused by cataracts.
</P>
<P>
However, only 2.1 million cataract operations and artificial
lens implants were performed in the 1988-1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The health minister admitted that reducing the number of
cataract sufferers "remains a major challenge to the country's
medical community" because of the limited economic resources and
inadequate technology.
</P>
<P>
There are no independent ophthalmology services in about 500
counties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also attending today's ceremony were He Luli, vice chairwoman
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress; State
Councilor Wang Zhongyu; and Bai Lichen, vice chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The mission to Tibet is also an important part of "Sight First
China Action," a joint project launched by the Ministry of Health,
the China Disabled Persons' Federation and Lions Clubs
International in August of last year.
</P>
<P>
The project will undertake 1.75 million cataract operations
within five years and should be able to complete 450,000
operations annually by 2001, according to Tam Wing Kun, executive
committee chairman of Sight First and board appointee of Lions
Clubs International.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250 national and provincial medical teams will go to
remote and poverty-stricken areas during the project. Some 348,000
operations were performed in China last year, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
