<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Request to Resume Arms Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz on Thursday turned down a request by the chief
U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler to resume arms inspections, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission for disarming
Iraq, known as UNSCOM, sent a letter to Aziz asking Iraq to allow
the resumption of arms inspections that Iraq suspended on August
5.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted Aziz as responding that "Butler and some elements in
the Special Commission are not international officials but serve
the U.S. policies to maintain the sanctions on Iraq by following
its orders."
</P>
<P>
"The decision (to suspend U.N. arms inspections in Iraq) is
firm and will not change until the Security Council considers
Iraq's legitimate demands seriously, responsibly, honestly and
away from U.S. pressure and blackmail, and immediately lifts
sanctions off Iraq," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Security Council asked UNSCOM and the
International Atomic Energy Agency to continue arms inspections
when replying to their letters asking for guidance from the
Council after Baghdad's announcement of suspension of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad's announcement came on August 5 after the breakdown of
disarmament talks between Butler and Aziz on August 3. Aziz said
Butler' refusal to certify that Iraq has destroyed all its
prohibited weapons led to the collapse of their talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions on Iraq cannot be lifted unless UNSCOM
verifies that it is free of nuclear, chemical and biological
weapons and long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted Aziz as accusing Butler of "deliberately exercising
a policy of maneuvering, foot-dragging and confusion between
substantive issues relevant to the requirements of disarmament and
minor sham issues."
</P>
<P>
"We do not trust Butler, nor do we trust the elements
controlling the Special Commission, and we do not believe that the
resumption of work with them would be of any use," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz's comment came just before the Security Council is to
hear the briefing of Prakash Shah, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's special envoy to Iraq, on his talks with Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Shah held talks last week in Baghdad with Aziz on a mission of
trying to persuade Iraq into agreeing to allow the resumption of
U.N. arms inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq insisted that the Security Council must look
into its legitimate demands before it can change its position.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been claiming that the United States is manipulating
U.N. inspections to prolong sanctions on it, and that it has
complied with all relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
