<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Free Market Principles Not to Be Changed: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) reaffirmed
here Thursday that Hong Kong will not depart from its traditional
free market economy principles.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the SAR government's action last Friday of drawing
on its hefty foreign exchange reserves to counterattack
speculators in the stock and futures markets, Tung said that the
SAR government is not out there to support the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon organized by the Australian Chamber of
Commerce, Tung said: "We are not there to support the stock market
at any level. Neither are we against people taking short
positions on the stock market."
</P>
<P>
"What we do take is that when we see there are manipulations in
our foreign exchange market which create conditions and high
interest rates which enables the same people to take huge
positions in the short market they have created," the chief
executive said.
</P>
<P>
"That is something which is not acceptable to us. So our effort
is a very narrow effort, it is very defensive effort targeted
specifically at this particular action, and no more than that," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"As long as those conditions exist, we will do it," he said.
"We will do it at the right time when it is necessary to protect
our currency market, to protect our stock market -- the integrity
of our market needs to be protected," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's economy, Tung said that Hong Kong is
really having a very difficult time.
</P>
<P>
"Our second quarter GDP growth - the figures will come out next
week - will be negative. The third quarter and the fourth quarter
will be very, very difficult and I think difficulties will go well
into next year, into 1999," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen, during the past few months, substantial
correction in our property prices, in our stock market. We have
also seen unemployment going up and I know, unfortunately, it will
continue to go up in the months ahead," Tung added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the Asian financial turmoil has really impacted
Hong Kong, as it has done with other communities and nations in
the region, in a very, very serious manner.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Asian turmoil has now affected other emerging
markets, whether it is Russia or South America and that "if we
don't, in Asia, get things right, the impact is not just to Asia,
to the emerging markets, to Russia - I think it will impact
Australia and New Zealand - it will impact all the rest of the
world also".
</P>
<P>
So it is not just an Asian problem, it is a global problem that
really needs some global solutions, Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Hong Kong's future, Tung said that it will not be
all doom and gloom as some people predicted because of the SAR
government's prudent and effective financial management and its
huge fiscal reserves.
</P>
<P>
"We have a civil service whose head is really screwed-on,
working very hard, totally uncorrupted," he said. "We have a
society which gives great emphasis to the rule of law."
</P>
<P>
"Our investment in education which is so important to our
future is continuing, and will continue as we move into the 21st
century because we know that without the quality of people, we
will not be competitive and in a knowledge-based society, nothing
is more important than that," he continued.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government also puts 235 billion HK dollars (30 billion
U.S. dollars) in infrastructure projects over the next five years,
of which 100 billion HK dollars (13 billion U.S. dollars) will be
in the railway expansion program, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Despite such a difficult economic climate, the SAR government
is still committed to these investments because Hong Kong has good
solid foundations and the Hong Kong people have confidence in
their own future, the chief executive said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grand Prix Could Be Back to S. Africa in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Formula One racing may
return to a South African racing circuit in 2001, South African
media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Formula One Association president Bernie Ecclestone announced
Wednesday that South Africa will host official Formula One test
sessions in 1999 and 2000 attended by all race teams, in
preparation for a full world championship event in 2001.
</P>
<P>
This came as a disappointment to South African motorsport
circles which expected the global motor showpiece to be back as
soon as next year. The last Grand Prix South Africa hosted was in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone, who met President Nelson Mandela for lunch
Wednesday, said the reason South Africa probably would not host
an F-1 race before the turn of the century was a lack of space on
the F-1 calendar.
</P>
<P>
Current agreements with the racing teams allow for 16 races
per season. This is expected to be increased to 17 next year and
18 the year after, but that still doesn't guarantee South Africa
a race.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreements with 16 countries which currently stage
rounds of the F-1 world championship. In addition, we have
agreements with five countries - including South Africa - who are
waiting for dates to become available," Ecclestone said.
</P>
<P>
He said his aim was to see South Africa hosting a round of the
F-1 world championship in 2001. But the possibility of South
Africa hosting Grand Prix earlier than that was also not ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
The F-1 boss said he and Mandela did not discuss South
Africa's impending legislation to ban tobacco sponsorships or its
impact on F-1 racing.
</P>
<P>
But he denied that South Africa's chances of hosting a Grand
Prix would be hurt by the government's new tough stance against
tobacco advertising. He said this was not even a consideration.
</P>
<P>
The South African cabinet has approved a bill which proposes
heavy fines for anyone who advertises tobacco products or brands
through sponsorships or donations.
</P>
<P>
Formula One is heavily sponsored by tobacco companies, with
some estimates placing its support in excess of 400 million U.S.
Dollars a year..
</P>
<P>
Ecclestone said he felt South Africa would adopt international
trends by phasing out F-1 tobacco sponsorship over a period
through to 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Coach Warns South African Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- South African national
soccer team have the potential to dominate Africa but local
soccer officials must first get rid of their hidden agendas and
political in-fighting, former national coach Jomo Sono said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sono, who amazed South Africans when he led the national team
to the final of the African Nations Cup in February, said he did
not believe the South African Football Association (SAFA) is now
really trying to select a suitable new national coach, South
African media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SAFA is expected to name the new head coach early next month.
Former coach of top English club Chelsea, Dutchman Ruud Gullit,
and former Nigerian World Cup coach, Yugoslav Bora Milutinovic,
are tipped to be among the candidates.
</P>
<P>
"All this business of advertising the post of head coach is
cosmetic. I'm sure they have already made up their minds about
who will be appointed and are only going through the motions in
calling for applications," Sono said.
</P>
<P>
Sono, a former soccer star and now owner and coach of local
professional soccer league club Jomo Cosmos, said he firmly
believes South Africa can eclipse Nigeria as the continent's top
dogs.
</P>
<P>
"We need the right coach and although Nigeria have better
individual players, we could build a team that could beat them,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we have to stop the politics inside our game and stop the
hidden agendas that go on under the table if we are to succeed,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The latest FIFA rankings showed that South Africa had dropped
to fifth place in the continent. This was largely due to its
failure to make an impact in the World Cup in June and its loss
of African Nations Cup crown to Egypt in February.
</P>
<P>
The South Africans were ousted at the group match stage on
their World Cup debut in France after mustering only two points
off two draws against Denmark and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Sono said he would make sure certain conditions are met if he
is to take the job again, including the permission for him to
install his own technical and management team.
</P>
<P>
He would also take the team only on a part-time basis and
would not accept any interference in the way he runs the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
