<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Progress to Probe of Nairobi Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Director of the U.S. Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) Louis Freech is to arrive here
Thursday evening as the Kenyan-U.S. probe team has held three
more suspects involved in the August 7 Nairobi bombing.
</P>
<P>
A reliable source, on condition of anonymity, told Xinhua
Thursday that the three have been arrested since last weekend,
raising the total number of the bomb suspects currently detained
in Nairobi to at least nine. He did not reveal their
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
The figure includes the five detained by the investigators
before last Friday and Mohammed Saddiq Howaida, the key suspect
arrested in Pakistan on the day of the bombings and then flown
blindfolded back to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The source said the FBI chief, who will arrive here at between
5:00 p.m. and 6:00 p.m. local time Thursday from Tanzania, is
scheduled to tour the bombing site in downtown Nairobi Friday and
then hold a press conference on the progress of the bomb blast
investigation.
</P>
<P>
So far, it is unknown if the other two suspects reportedly
arrested by the Pakistani authorities this week have been handed
over to Kenya or not.
</P>
<P>
The two men, identified as a Saudi and a Sudanese, were
arrested while trying to cross into Afghanistan from Pakistan
with fake Yemeni passports, a local media report quoted Pakistani
immigration officials as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Freech, during his one-day visit in the Tanzanian capital of
Dar es Salaam Thursday, said that the investigation into the
bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania is making
progress, but it's too early to make any conclusion.
</P>
<P>
The car bomb attack at the U.S. embassy in a very busy
commercial area in Nairobi killed at least 253 people and injured
some 5,000 more.
</P>
<P>
A nearly simultaneous car bombing outside the U.S. embassy in
Tanzania killed 10 people and wounded at least 70 others.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan-U.S. joint probe team raided the Hill Top Hotel on
Tuesday, where the bomb -- 800 kilograms of highly explosive TNT
-- was believed to be assembled.
</P>
<P>
Two rooms at the hotel were reportedly rented by four bomb
suspects -- two Palestinians, one Egyptian and one Saudi Arabian
-- from August 3 to August 7.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said that Howaida, who checked in the Hill
Top Hotel on August 4, had five accomplices but three of them
died in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Howaida, a 34-year-old Palestinian from Jordan, left Nairobi
on August 6 and was arrested at the Karachi airport on the
following day, the day of the deadly blast, because immigration
officials noticed his face did not match that in his passport.
</P>
<P>
Howaida reportedly said that he was an engineer who had been
sent to Kenya to provide technical and logistical support for the
bombing, but that he had been instructed to leave Kenya hours
before the blast.
</P>
<P>
He also said the bombing was sponsored by Saudi millionaire
Ossama bin Laden, whose group consisted of 4,000 to 5,000
heavily-armed terrorists who operated full-time in Saudi Arabia,
Sudan, Egypt, Yemen, Ethiopia, Somalia, Pakistan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has demanded Bin Laden's extradition
from Afghanistan, warning the Taliban government that it can
expect no international recognition until it hands him over.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban rejected the U.S. request, according to reports
from Islamabad, Pakistan's capital.
</P>
<P>
"We will never hand Ossama over to anyone and protect him with
our blood at all cost," the Afghan Islamic Press quoted Taliban
Chief Mulla Mohammad Omar as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
