<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Level Rising Near East China Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The sea level near the coast of
east China's Zhejiang Province has been rising at a rate of two
millimeters a year for the past four decades, according to a
maritime scientist.
</P>
<P>
Ying Renfang, director of a research program on the rising sea
level near Zhejiang, said that the present rate is expected to
increase in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The research project, sponsored by the National Oceanography
Bureau, is exploring the relationship between the rising sea
level and the El Nino phenomenon, and will recommend a series of
measures to prevent possible harmful effects brought about by the
rising sea.
</P>
<P>
Ying said the rising level could cause serious typhoon and
flooding, and change the ecological environment of the coast.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Shanghai, Tianjin and Guangzhou have launched
similar studies in this regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
