<HEADLINE> Former Iranian Minister Denies Taking Commissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian Minister of Mines
and Metals Hussein Mahluj has denied that he and his deputy Ali
Shekarriz have received commissions in purchase deal, local daily
Tehran Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the daily, Mahluj rejected the report against
him carried in the latest issue of the Arzeshha (values) weekly.
</P>
<P>
The daily gave no details about the content of the letter, but
said the letter was also faxed to the State Audit Office (SAO),
the body in charge of the investigation into the alleged
embezzlement cases in the Mines and Metals Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Weekly has said that the SAO has found Mahluj and Shekarriz
guilty of taking 540,000 German marks (337,500 U.S. dollars) in
commission in a purchase deal of aluminum machinery for their
ministry when looking into alleged embezzlement cases in the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The weekly also said the two officials have confessed to the
offense and the SAO has ordered them to return the money to the
state treasury.
</P>
<P>
And Mahluj is trying to convince the SAO to abort the ruling on
him as he is likely to be appointed ambassador to South Africa,
the weekly said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the SAO has sent a letter to the weekly's managing
director, saying that the case was still under investigation and
no final verdict on the former minister have been issued.
</P>
<P>
The SAO letter also said that Hashemi and Ghafurifard were not
found involved in any of the embezzlement cases.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's relevant laws, government officials
are prohibited from accepting commissions on state dealings.
</P>
<P>
However, the SAO only has the right to ask for the return of
the money and the judiciary can issue verdict to punish the
violators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
