<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moving People For China's Largest Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Over 45,000 people who had to
make way for China's largest hydro-electric power station this
century have been relocated this month..
</P>
<P>
Located on the Yalong River in southwest China's Sichuan
Province, the Ertan Hydro-Electric Power Station will have six
generating units each with a capacity of 550,000 kw. The first
generating unit has gone on line earlier this month on a trial
base.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir behind the dam began accumulating water in May,
submerging villages in 5 cities and counties and over 2130
hectares of farmland, and thus displacing 45,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement project designed for these displaced people is
known as the "Ertan Model" and is being conducted in strict
accordance with World Bank standards, which provided a loan of 93
million U.S. dollars for the construction of the station, sources
here said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the displaced people have been moved into new homes and
received financial compensation and land.
</P>
<P>
A new county seat and eight townships have been completed for
them. Since 1995, two billion yuan has been allocated for the
resettlement project and work has been done to meet the people's
material and cultural needs, according to Wang Chunyun, deputy
magistrate of Yanbian County.
</P>
<P>
As the water level continues to rise, more people are expected
to need to be relocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
