<HEADLINE> No EU Additional Fund for Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A European Commission official
said on Thursday that the executive body of the European Union had
no planning for additional financial aid for Russia right now.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokesman Verros Constantin told the press that the
European Council of Ministers had already drawn the line that all
commission financial aid would be channeled via either the World
Bank or the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
He said: "The commission continues to support the IMF aid
package."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Commission President Jacques Santer had
asked commission services to study ways as to how to assist Russia
to get out of its crisis of budgetary stability.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission will meet on September 3, immediately
after its summer recess, to discuss the development of situation
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The commission is willing to offer assistance in the country's
restructuring," said the official, "but the Russian authorities
have to do their part."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the Russian central bank and monetary
monitoring authorities still need to do more to render outside
assistance effective.
</P>
<P>
When asked what tangible assistance the commission is
providing, the official said that the European Union has been
helping Russia through the TACIS technical assistance program.
</P>
<P>
The TACIS technical aid program is aimed at helping the central
and eastern European countries as well as Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
