<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela, Nujoma Discuss D.R. Congo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- South African and Namibian
heads of state were locked in talks Thursday morning over the
crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and conflicting
positions in the region on its resolution.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, accompanied by two senior ministers,
arrived at South African President Nelson Mandela's office in Cape
Town for talks with Mandela and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, fresh from a two-day
diplomatic mission to Rwanda and Uganda along with Defense Minister
Joe Modise, was also present.
</P>
<P>
An Ugandan special envoy, Foreign Minister Amana Mbabazi, was also
expected in Cape Town for talks with South African senior officials.
</P>
<P>
A presidential aide said Nujoma had requested the meeting to brief
Mandela about a separate Zimbabwean-led initiative to resolve the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is part of a seven-nation committee, set up at Victoria
Falls in Zimbabwe on August 8, which investigated DRC President
LaurentB}abila's claims that the rebel uprising in his country was
being backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Zambia, Angola and Namibia Wednesday indicated they
would assist Kabila with arms and troops to quell the revolt.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has rejected military intervention and believes a
peaceful solution to the crisis is still possible. It is believed that
South Africa is pushing for a meeting of all political parties in the
DRC to broker peace there.
</P>
<P>
The Congo rebels, who have made rapid military advances in the DRC,
indicated Wednesday that they would be willing to negotiate a
cease-fire with Kabila's government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
