<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Political Groups Refuse to Register </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of about 100
newly-emerged political associations have rejected the idea they
should be screened and registered by the government before they
can participate in the country's new democratization process as
political parties.
</P>
<P>
They made their position known in a meeting with the
Independent Electoral Commission (INEC) Wednesday in Abuja, the
federal capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the All Nigerian Congress and 20 other
political groups in the south, former governor of Oyo State,
Chief Bola Ige said there was no need for registration of
parties.
</P>
<P>
"Political parties formed by citizens need to be recognized by
INEC," he was quoted by the Post Express newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He also said that since the government would not fund the new
parties, there was no need for the government to monitor their
finances just as there should be no rules to govern the parties
except the rules for campaigns.
</P>
<P>
On the elections, he suggested that all the polls should take
place at about the same time, as well as the handover in all
tiers of government.
</P>
<P>
Ige also rejected the idea of screening candidates by the
secret police, State Security Services (SSS), saying that once a
candidate meets the criteria in the constitution of the country,
he should be eligible to contest for election.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the INEC should be enlarged so that all the
parties will have their representatives in it.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Ige's position received almost
universal support from the political groups, who then followed by
one and another in making one or two additions of their own.
</P>
<P>
The INEC chairman, Justice Ephraim Akpata, however, insisted
that political groups must be registered as it is demanded by the
law.
</P>
<P>
He cited provisions of the Decree No. 17 of 1998 which
establishes the INEC and the 1995 draft constitution to support
his point.
</P>
<P>
"We are independent, but certainly not above the law and we
should not be seen to subvert it," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new transition to civil rule program
announced by Nigerian military leader, General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, the country will hold a presidential election in the
first quarter of 1999, while the new civilian president will
assume office on May 29, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
