<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes Currency Devaluation Rumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China today strongly refuted
rumors that its currency will be devalued and reaffirmed that
the yuan will remain solid.
</P>
<P>
"Recently, especially since August 3, there has been a sudden
renewal of rumors that the yuan will be devalued, and this is
rather confusing," Li Fuxiang, deputy director of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange, told a seminar on the Asian
financial crisis and the development of financial markets in the
Chinese mainland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that China's balance of international payments
remains strong, that the internal economic structure and economic
fundamentals have not changed significantly, and that no new
factors affecting the exchange rate of the yuan have emerged, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of yuan-devaluation rumors under this sort of
situation is an abnormal phenomenon," he said.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the yuan is determined by basic
economic factors, Li said, adding that China's exports still have
great potential yet to be tapped, and overseas investors are
confident about China's economic prospects.
</P>
<P>
Li also said China's foreign debt structure is reasonable and
that its huge foreign exchange reserves, which were valued at more
than 140 billion U.S. dollars at the end of June, have provided a
firm backing for the yuan's stability.
</P>
<P>
"It's unwise and unnecessary to devalue the yuan, and the yuan
will not be devalued," Li noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
