<HEADLINE> Technicians Help Two Million Farmers in Shaanxi Out of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Some two million farmers in
northern Shaanxi Province in northwest China have bid farewell
to poverty, thanks to the help of agricultural technicians from
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 25 poor counties in the region, which
was China's old revolutionary base, farmers had an average annual
net income of 923 yuan in 1997, as against 440 yuan in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A scientific poverty-alleviation program, initiated by the
Ministry of Science and Technology and certain local departments
in 1990, helped provide the region with thousands of agricultural
technicians from both inside and outside the province.
</P>
<P>
"The technicians are good advisers for the farmers," said Cao
Jiuwang, a 55-year-old farmer who became better-off after
attending training classes organized by the technicians.
</P>
<P>
Cao is only one of the 800,000 beneficiaries of various kinds
of training classes, said a local official.
</P>
<P>
"More agricultural technicians will be assigned to help
implement the program within the next three years so that
the region's 500,000 farmers still living under the state-set
poverty line can get out of poverty before the end of the
century," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
