<HEADLINE> Russia's Gold, Currency Reserves Down 11 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia's gold and foreign
exchange reserves dropped by 11.2 percent in the week before the
effective devaluation of the ruble earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The reserves went down from 17 billion U.S. dollars on August 7
to 15.1 billion dollars on August 14, Russian central bank said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government and the central bank Monday raised the
ruble exchange corridor from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the dollar,
which amounted to a devaluation of the national currency.
</P>
<P>
The official exchange rate set by the central bank Thursday
was 6.99 rubles against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The bank has spent about 3.8 billion dollars to prop up the
ruble and the Monday move was to preserve the country's gold and
currency reserves, the governor of the central bank Sergei Dubini
said. 
</P>
