<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transport Costs Lowered in African Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) has lowered transport costs
by liberalizing and harmonizing regimes and reducing bottlenecks
in the transport sector.
</P>
<P>
Africa Recovery, a publication of the United Nations, reported
in its latest issue that COMESA has made substantial progress in
simplifying, modernizing and harmonizing customs and transit
procedures, thus facilitating and improving transport and trade.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA Assistant Secretary-General for the program,
Sindiso Ngwenya, said that harmonization is essential for the
creation of a single and liberalized market.
</P>
<P>
He said, this has helped to bring down transport costs and
make headway towards a free trade area, expected to be
established by the year 2000, adding that COMESA is also expected
to establish a customs union by 2004.
</P>
<P>
The report said the reduction of trade tariffs and customs
duties have contributed to an increase in intra-COMESA and
third-party trade and the harmonized transit regimes have also
played a crucial role, encouraging profits and economic growth
among the member countries.
</P>
<P>
Trade among COMESA countries was worth 2.7 billion U.S.
Dollars in 1997, compared to 834 million U.S. Dollars 12 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth of trade with third parties averaged 7.1
percent and economic growth reached 4.5 percent in 1997, the
highest recorded over the last 10 years in the economic grouping.
</P>
<P>
COMESA was established in 1994 on the basis of the
preferential trade area for eastern and southern africa with over
20 member countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
