<HEADLINE> China to Import Traffic Monitoring System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China plans to import an
advanced traffic monitoring system from the United States by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The plan was announced during a recent Shanghai symposium
sponsored by the Shanghai Municipal Communications and
Transportation Association, Nanfang Satellite Telecommunications
Service Co. Ltd. from Guangdong Province, and US-base Qualcomm
Incorporated.
</P>
<P>
Qualcomm developed the monitoring system -- Omni TRACS -- on
the basis of patented CDMA technology. The system will use
satellites to transmit two-way information on a 24 hour basis and
provided accurate positioning reports involving accidents and
various other highway emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Omni TRACS has been introduced to more than 30 countries and
regions since 1989. The system has played a major role in
improving the efficiency of highway communications, transportation
and managing the flow of materials.
</P>
<P>
China has built 3,000 km of expressways since the
Shenyang-Dalian Expressway, the first in the country, opened to
traffic in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for increasing the length of operational expressways
to 6,500 km by the year 2000. China engaged in an extensive effort
to spur economic development by allocating massive funding to
develop infrastructure, including the expressway and highway
networks.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the new system to enhance the nation's
management expertise related to highway communications and
transportation. They noted the system will have a profound impact
on the nation's transportation sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
