<HEADLINE> Technological Development Called for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Guangzhao, vice chairman of
the National People's Congress Standing Committee, today called on
young Chinese scientists worldwide to make greater contributions
to the country's scientific and technological development in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, chairman of the China Science and Technology Association
(CSTA), issued the appeal at the opening ceremony of the third
CSTA annual meeting of young scientists.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China must substantially increase the
production of grain, meat, sugar, aquatic products and cooking
oil in order to meet the needs of its growing population
which is expected to hit 1.6 billion at some point around the year
2040.
</P>
<P>
Zhou noted limited possibilities for expanding arable land and
stressed the solution to the problem will lie in relying on the
development of agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has sent a large contingent of young
students abroad for advanced studies over the past 20 yeas, with
the figure supplemented by a significant number of self-sponsored
students.
</P>
<P>
Zhou added that a substantial number of students have returned
and are playing an important role in China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Young scholars remaining abroad have provided diversified
scientific technological services for the motherland, according to
Zhou.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to help overseas Chinese scientists
learn more about China's most recent scientific and technological
developments and introduce avenues enabling them to contribute to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The 700 young scholars and experts attending the three-day
meeting to promote academic exchanges will discuss four major
topics -- information science and microelectronics, biological
science and technology, materials science and engineering, and
environmental resource and sustainable development technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
