<HEADLINE> Jordan Develops Biblical Sites to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordan is speeding up the
excavation and development of its bible-related sites as part of
its efforts to boost tourism, the semi-official Jordan Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The most prominent one of these sites is called "Maghtas" in
Arabic, where archaeologists believe John the Baptist performed
baptisms and Jesus Christ visited on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
Teams from Ministry of Tourism and Antiquities have been
excavating around the clock at the site on the eastern bank of the
River of Jordan and the site is open to tourists by the end of
1999, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the archaeologists are preparing for tourists
another site, where it is said that Jesus Christ spent a 40-day
retreat after his baptism.
</P>
<P>
The digging there has so far led to the discovery of ancient
churches, mosaic floors and ancient water systems, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a route used by Christian pilgrims
hundreds of years ago was found.
</P>
<P>
The route started from Jerusalem, passed through the River of
Jordan and ended in Madaba, 30 kilometers south to Amman.
</P>
<P>
Near Madaba is the Mount Nebo, where the Prophet Moses' burial
site is located and an ancient church, dating back to 560 A.D. was
discovered, in which a Byzantine mosaic map of the Holy Land was
found.
</P>
<P>
The government is working to make the route one of the most
attractive spots for travelers.
</P>
<P>
In northern Jordan, the paper said, there is another biblical
site named Um Qais. It is said that Jesus Christ performed the
miracle of the Gadarene swine there.
</P>
<P>
The religious sites may greatly help Jordan boost its tourism
if they are excavated, developed, advertized and protected
properly, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The bible-related sites, combined with religious ceremonies,
cultural and musical events, can make Jordan "an interesting
destination" for travelers, said Marwan Khoury, Managing Director
of the government-financed Jordan Tourism Board.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, which used to be Jordan's pillar industry before the
1991 Gulf War, set off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, has been
stagnant due to the instability in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
