<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan First Lady Janet
Museveni has opened a women's bank in Pakwach town in the
country's West Nile district.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from the President's Office
Thursday, the first lady who is on a two-day visit to the
district said the bank will help empower women in the area
economically.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which mobilized a capital of 10 million Ugandan
shillings (8,000 U.S. Dollars) from 1,154 women share-holders,
also received some assistance from the Private Sector Development
Program (PSDP).
</P>
<P>
It saves people from moving long distances with large sums of
money and also provides a number of facilities to rural women
which other commercial banks cannot provide to them.
</P>
<P>
Ephraim Kamuntu, the national coordinator of PSDP who was
accompanying the first lady, said that millions of Ugandans in
rural areas have no access to bank services, resulting in 33
percent of the money in circulation in Uganda outside the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
This bank will play a very big role in tapping such money and
put it in the bank system, he asserted. 
