<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Moves to Push Peace Process in Bougainville </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Papua New Guinea (PNG)
government Thursday withdrew the authority of the PNG Defense
Force to carry out military operations on the war-torn island of
Bougainville in a move to advance the peace process there.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet met yesterday and made the latest and bold
decision in terms of rescinding the call-out on Bougainville," PNG
Prime Minister Bill Skate was quoted by the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A call-out order originally made in 1989 authorized the
deployment of combat troops on Bougainville to support police
after sustained civil unrest on the island. The call-out was
renewed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leaders on Bougainville have been pushing for an end to
the call-out and are also demanding independence from PNG.
</P>
<P>
Skate said he hoped the decision to end the call-out would help
"achieve peace through peaceful means".
</P>
<P>
Asked if he expected that an end to the call-out would prompt
Bougainville rebels to disarm, Skate said: "That's the whole idea.
There must be trust. The Papua New Guinea government is doing its
part and we expect the parties on the other side will also do the
same."
</P>
<P>
The 10-year civil war on Bougainville ended this year with the
signing of the Lincoln Peace Agreement in New Zealand between the
PNG government and Bougainville rebels.
</P>
<P>
Skate said it was hoped that a date could soon be set for a
meeting of Bougainville leaders and the PNG government to further
discuss the peace process and move toward a reconciliation
government for Bougainville.
</P>
<P>
Bougainville leaders are now meeting at Buin, in Bougainville's
south, to determine a common position in future talks with the
Skate government, the AAP said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
