<HEADLINE> APEC Business Summit to Focus on Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Business Summit meeting in
Malaysia will focus on the financial crisis in Asia and steps to
restore investors' confidence in the region, officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting beginning on November 14 in Kuala Lumpur
would highlight critical issues related to the liberalization of
the global financial systems and the extent of the role and
contribution of APEC in addressing these problems, Abdullah Mat
Zaid, co-chairman of the organizing committee for the APEC
Business Summit Malaysia 1998, said at a press conference in
Petaling Jaya near here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The APEC Business Summit to be hosted by the APEC Business
Advisory Council (ABAC) would provide a golden opportunity for all
corporations, foreign and local, to strategize on how to deal with
the present economic contagion, the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, about 1,500 chief executives,
corporate leaders and economists from APEC members are expected
to attend the summit, which is also aimed at promoting business
and strategic alliances between entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said, "Identifying new business, investment and
technology transfer opportunities would also be accorded top
priority by corporate leaders."
</P>
<P>
He said frank discussions would also be held by leading
corporate leaders in the region on foreign direct investment
opportunities and how opportunities arise from the present risk
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
"New areas where foreign investors can benefit from direct
investments would also be closely examined," he added. 
</P>
