<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges Switzerland to Support, Protect Diplomats in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the United
Nations Office at Geneva (UNOG) Vladimir Petrovsky has called on
the Swiss authorities to help diplomatic missions of the least
developed countries by cutting the cost of living in the city of
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"Some of these missions can barely make ends meet due to the
high cost of living, which of course seriously hampers their ability
to perform their duties," Petrovsky told Swiss parliament members
at a seminar on the U.N. and Switzerland held at UNOG Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Support from Switzerland could considerably help to improve
the situation," said Petrovsky, who is also
U.N. under-secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the seminar, Petrovsky raised another issue of
major concern -- security, saying that "the diplomatic community
is increasingly concerned about its security" in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"Some diplomats are complaining loudly, thus damaging the image
of Geneva as a safe place for international interactions," he
said. "I believe that with the continued help and more active
involvement of the authorities of the host country we will be able
to solve this problem."
</P>
<P>
Affirming Switzerland's positive role in the history of
internationalism and its involvement with the U.N., Petrovsky
stressed that international organizations have also contributed
significantly to the identity of Geneva as a leading city in world
affairs, and they play an important role in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, a mutually beneficial synergy has emerged and it
provides a sound base for Geneva within the U.N. system," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
