<HEADLINE> ARATS Contacts SEF Concerning Death of Taiwan Businessman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) today supplied the Taiwan-based
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) with information concerning the
recent death of Wang Fujing, a 40-year-old Taiwan businessman who
died in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone (SEZ), Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Wang, a resident from Kaohsiung, was on the
board of directors for a Shenzhen packaging firm. Wang joined
three people, including his brother Wang Fukuan, chairman of the
company's board of directors, for supper on the afternoon
of July 12.
</P>
<P>
Wang left the group shortly after supper and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The company reported his disappearance to the local public
security bureau on July 15, and his body was discovered in a well
on Fenghuang Hill in the city's Bao'an District on the afternoon
of July 27.
</P>
<P>
Company representatives identified the body as that of Wang
Fujing on July 29, and a preliminary investigation by medical
experts cited suffocation as the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities arrested Wang Lei, a 25-year-old suspect, on
August 12. The alleged perpetrator, a native of central China's
Henan Province, worked as a security guard for the Jinfang
Mortgage Company located in the Futian District.
</P>
<P>
The suspect confessed his involvement in the crime perpetrated
on the evening of July 12. Wang Lei told investigators that Taiwan
resident Chen Rongbiao, the 28-year-old board chairman of a
mortgage company, hired him and another local resident to assist
Wu Wunshun, a 38-year-old Taiwan resident, in the murder.
</P>
<P>
He also told authorities that the murder took place in Chen's
home. The perpetrators removed the victims clothing and placed the
corpse in the aforementioned well. Chen paid the perpetrators
20,000 yuan for committing the heinous crime.
</P>
<P>
Chen Rongbiao and Wu Wunshun fled to Taiwan shortly after the
homicide and ARATS called on Taiwan law enforcement departments to
provide assistance in determining their current whereabouts and to
return the suspects to Shenzhen to answer questions concerning the
ongoing investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
