<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Hydro-Power Station Has Positive Ecological Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ertan Hydro-electric Power
Station, China's largest built in this century, will not only
provide a vast supply of electricity to southwest China, but will
improve the region's ecology as well.
</P>
<P>
The station's 101-sq-km reservoir, which went into partial
operation last week, is playing a vital role in adjusting the
climate of the surrounding mountain valleys of the Yalong River at
Panzhihua in Sichuan Province, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Because of this adjustment, the previously sub-tropical dry
climate is turning more humid, making it better suited for
vegetation and animal life.
</P>
<P>
After touring the area, a World Bank environmental protection
delegation noted that strict measures taken during the
construction have resulted in an improved environment, which will
be conducive to alleviating soil erosion and reinforcing control.
</P>
<P>
A round-the-lake tree belt costing more than 1.9 million yuan
(229,000 U.S. dollars) is believed to be especially good for
reducing water silt and controlling soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
An environmental center is also playing an effective role in
monitoring water levels, rainfall, water and air quality and
pollution, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
With a designed generating capacity of 3.3 million KW, the
Ertan power station will become fully operational next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
