<HEADLINE> French FM to Measure Openness of Iran During Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said Thursday that he will measure Iran's will for
openness and the force of resistance it has met with during his
forthcoming visit to this Asian country on August 22-23.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot let pass the chance of a real evolution of this
country which is at a strategic moment," he said in an interview
with the private Radio-Television Luxembourg, on the eve of
his visit to Teheran.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first visit by a French foreign minister to
Iran since 1990 when former Foreign Minister Roland Dumas paid a
visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also expressed his conviction in the intention of
Iranian President Mohammed Khatami to open up the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is about to measure what are the possibilities for the new
leaders to impose this line, because there is also the resistance
to this line, and that has the repercussions on a very great
number of problems or the conflicts which appear in this region,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the foreign minister will also discuss with
Iranian leaders the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Asked if it is possible for French President Jacques Chirac or
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to visit Iran in the foreseeable
future, Vedrine answered, "We will see. We are not there yet."
</P>
