<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- For the second day running,
most of the action in the Australian dollar was in offshore trade
with the unit hit hard after a failed attempt in New York to push
it through 60 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The currency limped into the local session Thursday over half a
U.S. cent lower with further downside imminent until a lift in the
yen helped hold it just above 59 U.S. cents for most of the local
trade.
</P>
<P>
It eventually closed the session here at 59.13 U.S. cents, well
down from Wednesday's 59.78.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the unit sank quickly in "wild and heavy" trade in
New York and, breaking its recent symbiosis with the yen, was also
sold against that currency.
</P>
<P>
"A big sell order last night in the London/New York time zone
basically took the Aussie from 59.95 to 58.95 in New York and we
believe it was a very large Aussie/sterling sell order," Brent
Aggar, associate director of foreign exchange at Macquarie Bank,
said.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the somber local mood Thursday morning was a weaker
New Zealand dollar, following a larger-than-expected easing of
monetary conditions by the Reserve Bank of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Aggar said the Australian currency was then oversold in
domestic trade, hitting a low of 58.87 U.S. cents before
rebounding to 59.25.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 84.52 yen, up from 86.26
Wednesday, while the local unit was buying 1.0600 German marks
from 1.0766. 
</P>
</TEXT>
