<HEADLINE> Tibet Reports 8.5 Percent Growth For First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region
registered an economic growth of 8.5 percent for the first half of
this year, and the regional government is striving for a 10
percent growth for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the domestic gross product (GDP) for the
January-June period in Tibet reached 2.67 billion yuan (322
million US dollars), up 8.5 percent over the same period last
year. The commodity retail price index dropped by 3.6 percentage
points, while the cost of housing was down 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial growth for the first half year increased by 4.4
percent, while foreign trade volume expanded by over 200 percent
to reach 71.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tax revenues during the first half were more than 269 million
yuan, (32.4 million US dollars), an increase of 26 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite natural disasters including snowstorms, drought and floods
which assaulted the region last winter and spring, agricultural
production remained stable. Officials expect another bumper harvest
this autumn, baring major natural calamities.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous regional government has set a goal of 10
percent economic growth for this year, and to meet this target it
plans to increase investment in infrastructures and major capital
construction projects in the remaining months. Home construction
will receive priority, officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
