<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Enforces New Rules on Marine Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- New regulations on marine
pollution that prohibit dumping of garbage at sea and place
controls on pollution from ships and boats into the marine
environment came into effect in New Zealand Thursday.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Minister of Conservation Nick Smith said in a
statement: "We have treated the coastlines and oceans as a dumping
ground for too long. It is timely in this International Year of
the Oceans that we lift our act and start treating the marine
environment with some respect. These new regulations are a huge
step forward and should be welcomed."
</P>
<P>
The new regulations place nationwide restrictions on dumping of
garbage including plastics, lining and package materials.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulations, ships or boats without a treatment
facility will not be allowed to discharge sewage closer than 500
meters to shore or to a marine farm, or if the depth of water is
less than five meters. Those with a treatment system are allowed
to discharge anywhere except within 100 meters of a marine farm.
</P>
<P>
The regulations provide a nationwide benchmark but regional
councils will be able to increase the 500 meters distance from
shore and five meters depth provision by a rule in the regional
coastal plan.
</P>
<P>
The regulations also control the discharge of oil and noxious
liquids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0172 </DOCNO>
