<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Women Are Gainfully-employed in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- More women in Sweden are
gainfully-employed than men, according to Statistics Sweden on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of gainfully-employed women between the age of 20
and 64 rose to 78 percent in 1970-97 while the corresponding
figure for men dropped from 90 to 84 percent, the organization
said in its latest report on gender equality.
</P>
<P>
Women could shuttle between paid work and child care while men
enhance their working status with economic, political and union
power.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the narrowing employment gap, most working
women still carried the burden of child-rearing with 90 percent of
them taking days off in 1997 for child care. Men, on the other
hand, enjoyed better income and benefits and held 70 percent of
the seats in labor union boards, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
