<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher on Yen Short Covering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed higher Thursday on the back of the Japanese and Hong Kong
markets and institutions covering short positions.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed up 22.4 points, or 0.85
percent, at 2,658.5, off a low of 2,617.5.
</P>
<P>
"The yen was quite reasonable against the U.S. dollar and Hong
Kong was up from the start," senior dealer Peter Struk of Reynolds
&AMP; Co. said.
</P>
<P>
"There was a lot of short covering from institutions and some
good buy orders coming from overseas," he added.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, share prices closed lower but were pulled well clear
of their lows by the yen's rally against the dollar, brokers said.
The Nikkei 225 closed down 15 points at 15,391, well clear of the
low of 15,236.26.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng was trading 120 points higher at
7,742.5 led by sustained gains in futures amid rumors of further
government intervention to squeeze short positions.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all resources index closed up 7.2 points at
1,006.7 and the all industrials index closed up 40.9 points at
4,699.4.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 331.47 million valued at 1.097 billion
Australian dollars (647.23 million U.S. dollars), with 545 rises,
485 falls and 387 stocks remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp., which opened down, gained six
cents and its preferred scrip gained 14 cents.
</P>
<P>
Qantas Airways, which gained 11.9 points, surprised the market
to post a 20.6 percent lift in annual net profit despite negative
sentiment on Asia's impact.
</P>
<P>
Normandy Mining, which reported a 3.9 percent dip in annual net
profit but its core gold division increased its operating
contribution by 16 percent, gained four cents.
</P>
<P>
AMP, which has engaged Westpac Capital Markets to arrange its
domestic debt program, closed down two cents.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank gained 18 cents, ANZ rose 30 cents,
Westpac climbed 11 cents and Commonwealth Bank picked up 5.2
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed up 10.6 points, or 1.08 percent, at
988.8, gold closed 2.25 U.S. dollars lower to 283.85 an ounce.
</P>
