<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earliest Vascular Plant Found in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists
claim to have found the world's oldest vascular plant, dating
back 428 million years ago, in southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
This discovery is three million years earlier than that of the
Cooksonia, another species of senior plant dating back 425
million years, which was discovered in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Cooksonia has been generally accepted as the first vascular
plant on Earth.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yi, an expert with the Nanjing Palaeobotany Research
Institute attached to the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said that
about 428 million years ago this type of one-meter-tall plant with
feather-shaped twigs for leaves grew on the shore of a peaceful
bay, now the land of Fenggang County.
</P>
<P>
The plant was found by a team of Chinese scientists, including
two academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, in an
outcropping section at Dongkala in Fenggang County, 300 km from
Guizhou, capital city of Guizhou Province, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The plant has an academic Latin name -- Pinnatiramosus
Qianensis Geng -- and is the oldest reported vascular plant from
the Siliurian Period, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Wang reported his discovery to the public in an article
published by the British science magazine "Nature."
</P>
<P>
Wang and his team proved that the plant, which was sometimes
covered by tidal waves and sometimes stood above the smooth
sea water, is the earliest vascular plant species on Earth.
</P>
<P>
What the earliest vascular plants looked like, and when and
where they began to appear on Earth, are questions that have
concerned and interested many specialists for a long time, Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
"All land plants were the result of slow evolution of aquatic
plants." said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 70 percent of the newly discovered plant is made
up of single-trilete spores, most of which are characteristic and
dominate the structure of ancient vascular plants, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"The vascular plants could propagate themselves by their
spores," said Wang, and as a result it may be possible to find
many vascular plant species in southwest China, where scientists
have already found the earliest fossils of aquatic plants and
animals with complete skeletons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Hold Talks Without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
officials held three rounds of talks in the last few days but no
progress had been made concerning the long overdue Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank, it was disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiators Yitzhak Molcho held two rounds of talks
with Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qureia (Abu
Ala) in Jerusalem last week, the Israeli newspaper Haaretz
reported. He also met with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat in Gaza last Sunday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Molcho repeatedly offered the Palestinians
an area in the southern Judean Desert as part of a further West
Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
But both Arafat and Qureia rejected the proposal because Molcho
refused to reclassify the area an "Area B" which would eventually
become fully Palestinian territories under signed agreements,
Haaretz quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with Arafat, Molcho defended Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's refusal to give the nature reserve envisioned
by Israel an Area B status for fear of attacks from the
right-wing of his coalition, including National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the resumption of the Israeli-Palestinian talks last
month, Israel has refused, as it did in the past, to accept a
U.S. proposal which calls for an additional 13.1 percent Israeli
troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Molcho has routinely urged the Palestinians to accept
the Israeli proposal that Israel pullback from 10 percent of the
West Bank and designate a further 3 percent as a nature reserve,
where the Palestinians would only have limited powers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have insisted they would not accept the
proposal unless the so-called "nature reserve" would be clearly
classified as "Area B."
</P>
<P>
Sharon said in Tel Aviv Tuesday that Israel has agreed to
carry out the American initiative and withdraw from a total of 13
percent of the West bank, but senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat dismissed the statements as "maneuvers and games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
