<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First World Bank-Financed Highway in Xinjiang Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank-financed
Turpan-Urumqi-Dahuangshan top-grade highway in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region opened to traffic today.
</P>
<P>
The 283-km highway begins in Turpan, a well-known tourist city
south of the Tianshan Mountains, traverses westward through the
Tianshan Range via the town of Daban to reach Urumqi, and then
connects with the existing national highway at Dahuangshan after
turning eastward and passing Miquan and Fukang cities north of the
Tianshan Range.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the highway began in March 1995 and cost three
billion yuan (361 million U.S. dollars), including 150 million
U.S. dollars in loans from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The highway was built quickly and efficiently utilizing
standard international management and construction practices.
</P>
<P>
The new highway traverses a region of great potential for
economic development, with more than 180 large and medium-sized
enterprises along the way. The total industrial and agricultural
output value of these enterprises accounts for more than 60
percent of Xinjiang's total, and their combined gross domestic
product (GDP) make up 71 percent of the region's total.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, border trade between China and the
countries of Central Asia has continued to grow, with an annual
trade volume of 20 million tons, making transportation vital
and creating great pressure on the highway network.
</P>
<P>
Abdul'ahat Abdurixit, chairman of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Regional Government, said that the opening of the new highway will
effectively improve transportation in this remote region of China,
and will play a vital role in promoting local economic and social
development, and in creating a sound investment environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
