<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hemudu Museum Restores Neolithic Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Hemudu Museum has invested 11
million yuan (1.33 million US dollars) in a project to restore the
site of neolithic culture which lived in east China's Zhejiang
province some 7,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The project includes the restoration of living quarters and
workshops used by ancient ancestors and features displays of
relics discovered at the site and performances depicting their
daily activities.
</P>
<P>
The Hemudu Museum completed the first phase of the project back
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Hemudu Culture, the earliest neolithic culture thus far
discovered in eastern coastal areas, introduced the earliest
cultivated rice, wooden structures, fishing, painted pottery,
textiles, lacquerware, and jewelry made of jade, bone and the
teeth of various animals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Annual Growth Forecast Slashed to 0.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank, New
Zealand's central bank, Thursday slashed its forecast for the
economic growth of the country in the financial year ending next
March to just 0.1 percent from its previous forecasts of 2.2
percent in May and 2.8 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on monetary policy, Reserve Bank Governor Don
Brash said that the reason for the bank to have erred on its
earlier forecasting is international situation becoming "evidently
more serious".
</P>
<P>
"At the end of June, I suggested that the Asian crisis could
well constitute the most adverse shock to hit the New Zealand
economy," Brash said.
</P>
<P>
The expected growth of 0.1 percent in New Zealand's GDP in the
financial year would be the worst for eight years. The rapid
deterioration in the economy from three months ago sparked the
central bank to unveil a massive easing in monetary policy today.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Governor Brash announced that the Reserve
Bank cut the preferred level for the Monetary Conditions Index
(MCI) from 350 to zero.
</P>
<P>
The MCI measures the NZ dollar and interest rates. A lowering
of the bank's target level means it is approving recent falls in
the currency and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to a Wellington-based newspaper, the easing caused
wholesale interest rates to dive and helped put a rocket under the
share market.
</P>
<P>
"Lower interest rates boost spending and business investment,
helping pull the economy out of the doldrums," the Evening Post
said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Brash as saying that there is scope for
further easing, with the MCI likely to fall as low as negative
225 before rising slowly in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Brash, the Asian crisis, the fall of the Japanese
yen and the Australian dollar, and a shrinking of New Zealand
economy in the first half of the year are all factors in easing
monetary policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0189 </DOCNO>
