<HEADLINE> Yen Rises in Tokyo After Intervention Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese yen gained ground
against the dollar Thursday after Japanese vice finance minister,
Eisuke Sakakibara, warned that Tokyo was ready to intervene in the
currency markets.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar dropped to 142 yen level in Tokyo Thursday for
the first time in three weeks on fears of the market intervention
by Japanese financial authorities.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 142.54-56 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), down from 143.79-81 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 143.80-90
yen late Wednesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose to 144.20 yen during the morning, but fell to
142.28 yen later in the day after intervention fears were revived.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since July 30 the dollar was traded at the
142 yen level in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Market players stepped up yen buying after a senior Japanese
financial official reportedly said the yen's weakness has to be
corrected, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas fund operators and life insurers were major yen-buyers
during the day, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
One dealer said that the yen was supported by news that the merger
between the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) and Sumitomo
Trust and Banking Co. was on track.
</P>
<P>
News reports said that the government may provide public funds to
facilitate the planned merger and keep stability in the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
The market sentiment did not change, even though Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi denied that the government had decided to use funds for
LTCB, dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
