<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba's Quirot Beaten in 800 Meters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Ana Fidelia Quirot of Cuba
surfered an unexpected defeat to Letitia Vriesde of Suriname in
the women's 800 meters Wednesday at the Central American and
Caribbean Games in Maracaibo, Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Vriesde clocked in 2:00.24, followed by Mexico's Ana Gabriela
Guevara and Jamaica's Mardrea Hyman. While Quirot finished fourth
in 2:02.46.
</P>
<P>
Mexico maintained its lead in the walk competition with a
victory by Ignacio Zamudio in the 50-kilometer walk with a time
of 3 hours, 58 minutes and 15 seconds. The Mexican beat
Guatemala's Hugo Lopez by some 2,000 meters. It was Mexico's
third walking gold medal in the two-week long competition.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday also saw Mexico's Juan Pedro Toledo won the 200
meters, beating Cuban Misael Ortiz; Olympic champion Deon
Hemmings of Jamaica beat Andrea Balckett of Barbados in the
women's 400-meter hurdles; Jamaica's Morgan Deinsdale captured
the men's 400 hurdles; Jamaica's Beverly McDonald took the
women's 200, and Cuba's Norberto Tellez grabbed the men's 800
title.
</P>
<P>
Cuba topped the Games medals table with a total of 135 medals,
including 62 silver and 55 bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
Mexico comes on second with 49 medals and the host Venezuela
is third with 43 medals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
