<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long March 2C, 3B Become Major Carrier Rockets In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Long March 2C
carrier rocket carried two U.S. satellites into orbit today.
</P>
<P>
This follows the successful launch of a Long March 3B on June
13, carrying a Sinosat-1 telecommunications satellite of France's
Aerospatiale.
</P>
<P>
The two launches have helped establish the Long March 2C and 3B
rockets' usefulness for commercial satellites, analysts say. China
has put 9 Long March models into production, and the two types of
rockets have gained an international reputation and resulted in
many contracts.
</P>
<P>
The improved Long March 2C, which has a 2.5-ton payload, is
mainly used to carry satellites into their perigean orbit and
circular orbit.
</P>
<P>
The 3B, with a 5-ton payload, is China's most powerful carrier
rocket and is mainly used to carry satellites into geosynchronous
orbit.
</P>
<P>
The 2C made its debut on September 9, 1982. Improved models
have been used in 16 successful launches and have carried 21
satellites into orbit.
</P>
<P>
The 3B three-stage liquid-fuel heavy-thrust cluster carrier
failed in its first launch in 1997, but has had successful
launches after the model was improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
