<HEADLINE> France Backs International Conference on Great Lakes Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- France supports the holding of an
international conference on peace for the Great Lakes region in
Africa, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg (RTL), Vedrine
considered the idea, which was suggested by President Jacques
Chirac several months ago, as being "of greater importance than
ever."
</P>
<P>
Such a conference should include all the countries in the
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These countries should try to find together the conditions of
coexistence," he said in reference to the accusation by the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) that Rwanda and Uganda are
involved in the rebellion in the country.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine hinted that at present it is too early to say who
should at the conference represent the DRC, which is undergoing a
civil war between the government of President Laurent Kabila and
Tutsi Banyamulenge rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said France is neutral in the on-going conflict in the DRC,
although it thinks it is a regional conflict rather than one of
a single nation. 
</P>
