<HEADLINE> Flood-Stricken Province Vows to Help Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Education Commission of
Hunan Province in central China has vowed to help all its students
return to school by September 1, when the new semester begins.
</P>
<P>
The provincial education authorities have allocated 15 percent
of the province's total education budget to help rebuild flooded
schools, an official with the Provincial Education Commission
said today.
</P>
<P>
Serious floods this year have damaged over 20,000 schools in
the province, 734 of them destroyed or submerged by the floods,
according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
Because of this year's flooding, some 230,000 local students
were forced to stay at home, and schools closed their doors to
students earlier than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that Hunan may have nearly 600,000 students who
are in danger of becoming drop-outs because of the severe losses
suffered by their families.
</P>
<P>
Provincial education official disclosed that to date, a total
of 8 million yuan has been raised to rebuild flooded schools, and
non-flooded localities are also encouraged to lend a helping hand
to these schools.
</P>
<P>
Local health departments will make strict examinations of the
flooded schools to guarantee they are free from any potential
health hazards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
