<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Company Profits Higher Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Australian company profits
released here Thursday showed minimal signs of slowing in the
second quarter of this year, contrasting with previous surveys of
sentiment that showed business was feeling the pinch of the Asian
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Company profits rose 2.8 percent before income tax, net
interest and depreciation in the second quarter to 7.6 billion
U.S. dollars, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This came on the back of a strong first quarter, where profits
had risen a revised 9.3 percent from the 8.6 percent reported
earlier.
</P>
<P>
"It's a puzzle this number. It poses more questions than it
answers," Andrew Pease, senior economist with Nomura Australia
said.
</P>
<P>
"It's surprisingly strong and surprising in its composition,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
As about 60 percent of Australia's goods and services exports
go to Asia, business communities in Australia have been worried
about the impact of the Asian economic crisis on Australia.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Kirchner, senior economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS,
said it was too early to see the full impact of Asia on corporate
balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
"The full effects of Asia on corporate balance sheets will
probably not be seen until the second half of the year, as today's
profit results from Qantas illustrate," Kirchner said.
</P>
<P>
Australia's flagship air carrier Qantas Airways Ltd. has defied
Asia's economic turmoil and market expectations to produce a
stunning 20.6 percent lift in net earnings of 184 million U.S.
dollars for the financial year ending June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The airline's performance was underpinned by its domestic
airline operations and by further cost cutting, while the fall in
revenue from Asian services was offset by improved performances
mainly to the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
But Australia's tourism industry continued to feel the heat of
the Asian crisis as tourist numbers from Southeast Asia plunged by
28.8 percent last month to 39,600 and the numbers from northeast
Asia fell by 16.7 percent to 115,000 from the same month of last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
