<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria Sign Document of Oil Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Syria on Thursday
signed joint minutes to jointly rehabilitate an Iraqi-Syrian
pipeline and cooperate to promote oil cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency said the minutes was signed by Iraqi Oil
Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid and his Syrian counterpart Mohammed
Maher Jamal, who arrived in Baghdad on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rashid and Jamal on Wednesday held talks in Iraqi Oil ministry
and discussed the executive plans of the joint agreement signed in
last July during Rashid's Damascus trip.
</P>
<P>
Under the joint agreement, the two countries agreed to reopen
the pipeline from Iraq's northern oil fields in Kirkuk to the
Syrian port city Banias, and to construct a new pipeline with a
capacity larger than the current one to meet Iraq's exporting
requirements in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jamal's visit, the first by a Syrian oil minister in 18 years,
is another effort in the normalization of the bilateral
relations. During the Iran-Iraq War (1980-1988), Syria was the
only Arab state that sided with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
