<HEADLINE> Jordanian Waters Not Polluted by Israeli Sewage, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian waters in the Gulf of
Aqaba are not polluted in a sewage main break in Israeli coastal
city of Eilat, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Tests conducted by the Royal Scientific Society and some
independent environmentalists since August 17 did not find "any
noticeable pollution in our waters," Akef Abu Tayeh, vice
president of the Aqaba Region Authority said.
</P>
<P>
"We have been testing consistently since August 17 when the
Israeli Ministry of Environment informed us of the incident. The
tests over the last few days have not shown any deviation between
the samples and the water standards," the semi-official Jordan
Times quoted Tayeh as saying.
</P>
<P>
Israel Saturday closed all Eilat's beaches to the public after
an old sewage line broke down to send thousands of cubic meters of
raw sewage into the Gulf of Aqaba over the past days. The main
stopped the spewing of raw sewage Monday.
</P>
<P>
The e-coil bacteria in the Israeli waters in the gulf, partly
shared by Jordan and Israel, once reached 50 times the
internationally acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel have signed several agreements that bind them
to coordinate efforts to protect the environment of the Gulf of
Aqaba, home to some of the world's most spectacular coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
But most agreements and the subsequent exercises are focused on
containing the threat and damage of oil spilling.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian and Israeli officials will meet next Monday to
discuss preventive and contingent plans for sewage leaks, the
Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, residents in western Amman, capital of
Jordan, complained that water flowing out of their taps has odor
and contains worms, which has stirred a wide speculation of
polluting sources, including Israel.
</P>
<P>
The water pollution incident has led to the resignation of
Abdul-Salam Majali's government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
