<HEADLINE> Peace Project Collects 57,000 Arms in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 57,942 pieces of arms
have been collected in Mozambique ever since the start of the
Project of Transforming Arms into Ploughs in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Lucas Amosse, Secretary-General of Councillor of Mozambican
Catholic was quoted by media here as saying that the project,
which has been carried out mainly in the southern part of the
country, got wide support from the masses.
</P>
<P>
Amosse said that about one million U.S. Dollars, mostly from
non-governmental organizations, were spent on the program.
</P>
<P>
He said that because of the lack of financial back-up, the
project is still confined to the southern provinces of Maputo,
Gaza and Inhambane provinces.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to be extended to Zambezia in central
Mozambique and Nampula in the north.
</P>
<P>
In the 16 year-long civil war, a large number of weapons are
believed to be scattered among the citizens in the country, which
posing a threat to the social stability.
</P>
<P>
The transformation project is designed to exchange things like
bicycles, sewing machines and radios with weapons, and then turn
the weapons into ploughs and artifacts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
