<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Chief Inspects Bombed US Embassy in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 20 (Xinhua) - The Director of the United
States Federal Bureau of Investigation Louis Freech said here
Thursday morning that the investigation into the bombing of the
US Embassy is making progress, but it's too early to make any
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Freech, who was inspecting the damaged embassy premises, told
reporters at the destroyed U.S. embassy that the Tanzanian police
were very positive to cooperation with the FBI agents in
searching clues leading to perpetrators of the deadly bomb attack
on the US Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The FBI chief is expected to meet with his Tanzanian
counterpart Adadi Rajabu, Director of Criminal Investigation of
the Home Affairs Ministry, and other senior officials following
the site inspection which brings him into the main three-storey
building.
</P>
<P>
Freech, who arrived here Wednesday night from Washington, will
leave later Thursday for Nairobi, Kenya to visit the US embassy
there which was also hit heavily by a bomb attack nearly at the
same time on August 7.
</P>
<P>
About one hundred FBI agents have arrived here to work at the
bombing site since the car bomb blast which killed nine
Tanzanians and one Kenyan and injured more than 70 civilians
including seven Americans.
</P>
<P>
The US Secretary of States Madeleine Albright made a six-hour
visit Tuesday when she inspected the damaged embassy compound,
consoled victims of the bombing and held talks with Tanzanian
Vice-President Omar Juma and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
She confirmed more US emergency aid to Tanzanian victims
following the first batch of 100,000 US dollars worth of relief
supply, vowing to bring those behind the bombing to justice no
matter how long the investigation will take.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenneth Piernick, head of the FBI team here, said
that some important evidences collected at the scene have been
sent back to Washington for analysis.
</P>
<P>
Piernick, who is the Assistant Special Agent in charge of the
FBI Washington Field Office, said nothing could be found from the
video monitoring system at the embassy, which was working at the
time when the bomb went off, because there was no tape fitted in
the system.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian police have arrested 14 suspects following the
bombing, which was widely believed to be caused by a bomb hidden
at the Embassy's own water tanker as it was checked before the
blast.
</P>
<P>
But so far no breakthrough has been made and nothing has been
found related to the co-driver of the Embassy's truck, a blue
seven-ton Toyota water tanker, though he was believed to be the
key to the investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
