<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Troops Arrive in Kuwait for Joint Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Some 400 U.S. soldiers
arrived in Kuwait late Wednesday night, the first batch of a
1,500-member U.S. troops to take part in routine desert military
exercises with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The soliders were flown in from Fort Stewart, Georgia. The
remaining U.S. soldiers are expected to arrive during the next
three days.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Sean Frinnegan, Deputy Commander of the Doha Camp, the
Headquarters of the U.S. army in Kuwait, told reporters that the
soldiers would head to the camp immediately where they would have
six hours to draw prepositioned equipment and deploy in the desert.
</P>
<P>
The equipment, enough for a task force of around 1,200
soldiers, includes M-1 main battle tanks, M-88 Recovery vehicles,
Bradleys vehicles and military jeeps.
</P>
<P>
The games, code-named Intrinsic Action, are "designed to
provide continued U.S. ground presence and access in Kuwait,
enhance Kuwaiti defense capabilities and regional security," a
U.S. Embassy said in a news release issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The maneuvers also aim to strengthen relations, improve
inter-operability and battle staff proficiency between U.S. and
Kuwaiti forces, as well as enhance U.S. troops' capabilities to
rapidly deploy to the region, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The joint war games came amid increased tension in the region
caused by the latest standoff between Iraq and the United Nations
over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, Iraq announced suspension of cooperation with the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), complaining that it is
pro-U.S. and attempting to prolong sanctions, which were imposed
on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Members of UNSCOM have been conducting weapons inspections in
Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War, which ended the seven-month Iraqi
occupation of the oil-rich Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not be lifted until UNSCOM certifies that
Iraq has eliminated all weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
But a U.S. embassy spokesman has said the war games are "a
scheduled rotation of the Intrinsic Action forces and are not a
direct response to the current Iraqi confrontation with UNSCOM."
</P>
<P>
Colonel Finnegan said "this is a normal deployment and we do
that three times a year."
</P>
<P>
The exercises, which will last through November, was planned a
year ago and it had no political motive, he added.
</P>
<P>
The maneuvers are part of a 10-year U.S.-Kuwaiti defense pact
signed after the Gulf War, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
