<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Involved in UN Chief's Killing: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A South Africa commission
Wednesday revealed sensational evidence pointing to direct
involvement of former South African government in an
international plot to kill former UN Secretary-General Dag
Hammarskjold.
</P>
<P>
Hammarskjold died in September 1961 when his aircraft crashed
on its approach to Ndola airport in what was then Northern
Rhodesia (now Zambia), where he was due to meet Katangese rebel
leader Moise Tshombe to negotiate a truce in Congo's civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has found a set
of letters, contained in a batch of documents from South African
security archives, which reveal plans to blow up the UN chief's
aircraft, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The letters refer to the operation under the code name "How is
Celeste?" and also point to the involvement of the United States
Central Intelligence Agency and Britain's MI6 intelligence
agency.
</P>
<P>
The letters, some of which are hand-written and date from the
early 1960s, are on the letterhead of an organization called the
South African Institute for Maritime Research, which has a
Johannesburg address.
</P>
<P>
There is a current South African Institute of Maritime
Research, based in Simon's Town near Cape Town, which has links
with South Africa's state-controlled arms producer, Armscor.
</P>
<P>
One of the letters outlines the plan for the attack and refers
to the amount and type of explosives to be used.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish-chartered DC6-B Albertina carrying Hammarskjold
disappeared after the pilot had contacted Ndola airport and flown
over the landing site. It was later found crashed 10 kilometers
away from the airport.
</P>
<P>
The letters appear to be correspondence between two security
operatives who were directly involved in the plot.
</P>
<P>
The institute referred to in the letterhead is believed to
have been a front company for the South African military.
</P>
<P>
The TRC handed journalists copies of eight letters, dated
between July 12, 1960 and September 1961. They are marked
"confidential" and "top secret, your eyes only".
</P>
<P>
The TRC has handed the original documents to the government,
because the affair will have serious international repercussions
if the documents are found to be authentic.
</P>
<P>
Allegations that Britain had been involved in a plot to kill
Hammarskjold surfaced in Asian and African newspapers days after
the crash.
</P>
<P>
It was alleged that Britain was supporting Tshombe against the
UN. Tshombe declared the secession of the mineral-rich Katangese
province just two weeks after the Congo secured its independence
from Belgium on June 30, 1960 under the leadership of the
staunchly pan-Africanist and anti-colonialist prime minister,
Patrice Lumumba.
</P>
<P>
Hammarskjold, a Swede, was secretary-general from 1953.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Official on Sharing of Marcos Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Justice Secretary
Serafin Cuevas Thursday stood firm on his belief that a compromise
deal with the family of the late president Ferdinand Marcos is
still the best position the government can take to recover Marcos'
ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
Cuevas said the government is left without a better option
except engaging the Marcoses in a compromise settlement and
rejecting the idea of pursuing a court case to take back the money
hidden abroad.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is negotiating with the Marcos family
for 75-25 sharing of Marcos' deposits estimated at 5 billion U.S.
dollars, with the bigger amount going to the government.
</P>
<P>
About 570 million dollars of the Marcos wealth has been
returned to the Philippines by Swiss banks after 12 years of hard
work by the Presidential Commission on Good Government set up by
former president Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
However, the money, currently put under an independent account
of the Philippine National Bank, could be used only after the
Supreme Court and the Congress have decided on how to divide it.
</P>
<P>
Marcos ruled the country for 20 years. He was ousted in 1986 in
a popular revolt and died three years later in Hawaii, the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
