<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two More Held in Nairobi Bombing Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Two more suspects in the August
7 deadly bombing on the U.S. embassy in the Kenyan capital have
been arrested in Pakistan, the independent Daily Nation newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two men, a Saudi and a Sudanese, were arrested while
trying to cross into Afghanistan from Pakistan, the report quoted
Pakistani immigration officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said the suspects were carrying fake Yemeni
passports.
</P>
<P>
One of the men -- it was not stated which -- was said by
Pakistani officials to be "a pivotal participant" in the bombing
which killed at least 247 people and left some 5,000 injured,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
A near-simultaneous car bomb attack outside the U.S. embassy
in the Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam killed 10 people.
</P>
<P>
One of the suspects had been described by Mohammed Saddiq
Howaida, the suspect arrested in Pakistan on the day of the
bombings and flown blindfolded back to Nairobi, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"It is Howaida who led armed FBI (the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation) agents backed by Kenyan CID (Criminal
Investigation Department) officers to the seedy Hill Top Hotel in
Accra Road, Nairobi," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan-U.S. joint probe team confirmed Wednesday they
raided the hotel on Tuesday, where the bomb -- 800 kilos of high
explosive TNT -- was believed to be assembled. The hotel manager
now has been placed under arrest.
</P>
<P>
Two rooms at the hotel were rented by four bomb suspects --
two Palestinians, an Egyptian and a Saudi Arabian -- from August
3 to August 7.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said earlier Mohammed Saddiq Howaida, who
checked in the Hill Top Hotel on August 4, had five accomplices.
Three of them died in the bombing and two others were at large.
</P>
<P>
Howaida, a 34-year-old Palestinian from Jordan, left Nairobi
on August 6 and was arrested at the Karachi airport on the
following day because immigration officials noticed his face did
not match that in his passport.
</P>
<P>
Howaida reportedly said that he was an engineer who had been
sent to Kenya to provide technical and logistical support for the
bombing, but that he had been instructed to leave Kenya hours
before the blast.
</P>
<P>
He also reportedly said the bombing was sponsored by Saudi
millionaire Ossama bin Laden, whose group consisted of 4,000 to
5,000 heavily armed terrorists who operated full-time in Saudi
Arabia, Sudan, Egypt, Yemen, Ethiopia, Somalia, Pakistan and
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has demanded Bin Laden's extradition
from Afghanistan, warning the Taliban government that it can
expect no international recognition until it hands him over.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban rejected the request, according to reports from
Islamabad, the Pakistan capital.
</P>
<P>
"We will never hand Ossama over to anyone and protect him with
our blood at all cost," the Afghan Islamic Press quoted Taliban
chief Mulla Mohammad Omar as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Tuesday toured the
bombed U.S. embassies in Tanzania and Kenya to express grief for
U.S. and African victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
