<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 08:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's New Cabinet to Be Announced Soon, Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Chief of Royal Court Fayez
Tarawnhe, who has been entrusted with forming a new Jordanian
government, is expected to announce his cabinet soon, Jordanian
newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh will travel to the United States on Friday to consult
with King Hussein on the issue, semi-official English daily the
Jordan Times and Arabic daily the Ad Dustour both quoted informed
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The king is now at the Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minnesota, to
treat the cancer in his lymphatic tissue.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Hussein approved the resignation of the current
cabinet headed by Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali, which is
caught in a scandal of polluted drinking water in Amman and blamed
for a poor performance in domestic affairs, and entrusted Tarawnhe
to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Semi-official Arabic daily the Al Aswaq reported Thursday that
members of the new government will be named within 24 hours right
after the appointment of Tarawneh and some parliament deputies
might join the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Al Ra'I, another semi-official leading Arabic daily, Thursday
quoted informed sources as saying that Deputy Prime Minister for
Development Affairs and Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani is
expected to replace Tarawneh as chief of royal court.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh graduated from the University of Jordan in 1971. He
then obtained a master's degree and a doctorate in economics at
the University of Southern California, the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh served as assistant chief of Royal Protocol between
1971 and 1980 and then was appointed economic adviser at the
Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
In January 1988, he was appointed minister of state for prime
ministry affairs and in December transferred to minister of supply.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh left the government in 1989 and went to serve as the
board chairman of the Arab Contractors Company and meanwhile as a
member of the board of directors of the Industrial, Commercial and
Agricultural Company.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Tarawneh was named as a member of the kingdom's
delegation to the peace talks with Israel. While the talks were
still going on, he was appointed ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
He served the post in Washington from December 1992 until his
appointment as foreign minister on March, 1997, when Majali was
entrusted to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
In the February 18, 1998 reshuffle of Majali's cabinet,
Tarawneh was appointed chief of royal court.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, 49, also has a strong family background. His father
Ahmad Tarawneh, who just died on August 8 this year, once served
as cabinet ministers, parliament deputy and chief of royal court
from the 1950's to the 1970's. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
