<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Key Exports Down 2.3 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore key non-oil domestic
exports fell by 2.3 percent in July 1998 from the same month last
year, reversing June's 6.1 percent year-on-year growth, the Trade
Development Board (TDB) announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The weakness was even more visible in the total trade, which at
the current prices contracted by 8.4 percent in July compared with
the corresponding month of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports reached 7.6 billion Singapore dollars
(4.37 billion U.S. dollars) in July, registering an increase of
9.2 percent to the European Union and moderating its growth to the
United States to 3.6 percent from 16.7 percent a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports to Malaysia, Thailand and South Korea
slid by 13.1 percent, 11.2 percent and 28 percent respectively and
those to Japan and Hong Kong declined by 12.4 percent and 0.7
percent respectively. The growth of non-oil domestic exports to
China also moderated to 7.3 percent in July from 9.2 percent in
June.
</P>
<P>
The domestic exports of oil remained weak, plunging by 23.6
percent from July last year due to continued weakness in oil
prices arising from strong competition from regional refineries
since the start of the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports, a short term leading indicator of the
manufacturing sector, contracted further by 16.7 percent, the
fifth consecutive month of negative growth.
</P>
<P>
The weak underlying trend was also reflected in a 5-percent drop
in exports of Singapore-made electronics and the growth of non-oil
re-exports which moderated to 2.8 percent in July from 11.6
percent a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The trade board has projected that the country's external trade
will contract by 4.5-5.5 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
