<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Pledges to Improve Security in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni, who is on a working visit to the north, said Wednesday
the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) will be better equipped
to guarantee the security for people in the north.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the President's Office Thursday
morning said the president made the remarks to a public rally at
Boma Ground in Gulu town.
</P>
<P>
All those who are now in protected villages should return to
their villages when their security is guaranteed, Museveni was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Security has much improved since the rebels of Lord's
Resistance Army ran to southern Sudan after the UPDF overwhelmed
them recently, he added.
</P>
<P>
Local people were also urged to unite and fight those who
propagate the bad politics of division based on religion and
tribes.
</P>
<P>
The government's restocking program will first cover peaceful
areas and later spread out to those which are not yet peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said the government welcomes bandits to come out
peacefully and encourage elders and other leaders to contact rebels
and convince them to drop their arms.
</P>
<P>
When asked to improve the infrastructure in the region,
Museveni said the central government will build a network of
roads there, adding that the government is working with the World
Bank and Belgium to bring 3,000 telephone lines to Gulu.
Telephone services will be extended to Kitgum, Moyo, Adjumani and
Kotido later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
