<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 07:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Approves Largest Settlement Expansion on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel has approved a plan to
expand four settlements in the southern Golan Heights, the
largest expansion in the Golan since the current Likud government
came to power in 1996, Israeli newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee headed by National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon approved the projects Wednesday to build
2,300 housing units and 2,500 vacation units in the four
settlements.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's spokesman Raanan Gissin said the approval of the
construction was important for strengthening and developing the
Golan settlements and would create 5,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Gissin noted that the new communities would be located on the
slopes leading to Lake Kinneret, areas of vital importance to
protect Israel's water sources.
</P>
<P>
Sharon denied Wednesday night that the expansion would
undermine the resumption of peace talks with Syria, saying it
meant only expanding existing settlements. "This is in keeping
with the policy of this government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the expansion decision was originally reached
a month ago, but Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu urged Sharon to
delay it by a few weeks due to the visit of Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned that the expansion decision would have severe
consequences at a time when Syria was weighing the positive and
negative aspects of renewing talks with Israel, which broke down
in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Haaretz newspaper quoted an official Syrian newspaper as
saying Wednesday that peace talks with Israel would never resume
without an irrevocable Israeli commitment to a full withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
War.
</P>
<P>
The comments came in response to remarks made Tuesday by
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who called on Syria
to resume peace talks but said Israel would not give up the
entire Golan Heights under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai had been under heavy fire in the last few days since
he reportedly told a German news magazine that the depth of an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights should be linked with
the level of security Israeli obtains.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to his reported remarks, Netanyahu reiterated that
the Israeli government has not changed its policy on the Golan,
which he said was strategically vital for Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
