<HEADLINE> African Countries Trying to Stabilize Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe consulted a southern African regional delegation sent to
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) on the next steps to stabilize
the situation there, The Daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, also Chairman of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Organ on Politics, Defense and Security made the
consultations amid reports that several SADC countries were ready
to intervene militarily to block the DRC rebel advance on
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The decision was, however, not unanimous, with South Africa
and Botswana reportedly opposing the idea.
</P>
<P>
A SADC team of foreign ministers and military chiefs from
Zimbabwe, Zambia, Tanzania and Namibia has just returned from
DRC.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that they told the rebels that they
should accept a ceasefire to avert the possibility of regional
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Defense Minister Moven Mahachi Wednesday said that
ministers and officials of the SADC has agreed at a two-day
meeting in Harare to give the DRC government military support.
</P>
<P>
But South Africa and Botswana seem unlikely to be involved.
</P>
<P>
In Pretoria, a senior government official said South Africa
had not agreed to participate in any regional or SADC military
operation in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Later South African President Nelson Mandela went further in
opposing military involvement.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's Permanent Secretary for Foreign Affairs Ernest
Mpofu said Wednesday that the best solution would not necessarily
be intervention by a regional force, but by international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about a dozen rounds of heavy machine gun
fire were heard early Wednesday in the southwest of Kinshasa.
</P>
</TEXT>
