<HEADLINE> Provincial Management Of Flood-Relief Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, August 20 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province, which
has been hit by heavy flooding, has increased controls on
donations to see that the money and goods really get to the
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Ren Genshui, a provincial civil affairs official, says that the
province issued an emergency notice saying that donations need to
be handled in a clear, open, fair and orderly way and that they
are to be handed out for free, and that intercepting and holding
on to materials and diverting funds is illegal.
</P>
<P>
A hot line has also been opened to help the supervisory work,
Ren says, and they will send several teams to the worst-hit cities
and counties to supervise the distribution of relief goods.
</P>
<P>
The province has received more than 23 million yuan (2.8
million U.S. dollars) from Chinese and overseas organizations,
most of which will be used to help flood victims rebuild homes,
Ren says.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang, one of worst-hit cities, distributed a large number
of tents, timber, and tarpaper, and 5.85 million kg of rice, which
have helped 1.7 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
