<HEADLINE> Protecting Brand-Name Products in Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in Guangzhou,
the capital of China's Guangdong Province, has cracked down on
trademark and copyright violations in recent years to protect the
intellectual property rights of famous brands.
</P>
<P>
They began increasing protection of intellectual property
rights in September 1994 and have received 26 applications for
trademark protection and stopped 51 cases of trademark violation,
involving fake products worth 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of last year, Guangzhou customs officers
launched a special campaign to protect domestic band-name battery
products, leading to a remarkable increase in exports.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that exports of batteries from Guangdong will
amount to 170 million U.S. dollars this year, up more than 50
percent from the 1997 figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
