<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Board Opens Hearing on WNBA Union Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The National Labor Relations
Board (NLRB) opened proceedings in New York Wednesday on the
petition of the NBA Players Association (NBPA) to represent the
players of the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the NBPA, the WNBA, which
is sponsored by the NBA, asked to delay the election for a full
year until May 1999. The NLRB did not rule on the matter and
adjourned proceedings until August 27.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed that the league has asked to delay these
proceedings and the vote," said NBPA executive director Billy
Hunter. "The players are eager to obtain the rights to union
representation by the Players Association."
</P>
<P>
A majority of WNBA players agreed to form a union and filed a
petition for the NBPA to represent them earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Hunter said previously that the NBPA had received signed union
cards from close to 100 of the 120 WNBA players. "The players
have indicted their desire to unionize to exercise their rights
under the labor law, and the league cannot deny that or those
rights by legal maneuvers," said Ronald Shechtman, an attorney
representing the WNBA players.
</P>
<P>
"It's been the intention to organize this union for close to a
year now," said NBPA director of communications Dan Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
Hunter and the NBPA have done little negotiating with the NBA
since the league imposed a lockout on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Wasserman added the NBPA expects the women's collective
barganning agreement to be "a lot different than the men based on
the negotiations of the women's telling us what they want."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
