<HEADLINE> Thai Government Urged to Stimulate Retail Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's largest department
store Central Group has urged the government to prepare stimulus
measures as the retailing business is suffering from a drastic
decline this year, the Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Central Department Store Suthikiat
Chirathivat suggested that one possible measure the government
should consider is cutting Value Added Tax from 10 percent to 7
percent for consumers purchasing Thai goods.
</P>
<P>
This could help boost consumer spending and also support the
"Buy Thai" campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent comprehensive financial reform
package, which has won overwhelming public support, Suthikiat said
the government should also consider the drastic decline in
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the government speed up the duty free shop
policies that allow foreign visitors to apply for tax refunds when
purchasing goods in Thailand as is the case in many other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Thai department store sales last year fell by 20 percent from
1996 to 327.75 billion baht (8.19 billion U.S. dollars) and the
Thai Farmers Research Center predicted a further 10 to 20 percent
drop this year.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that sales in the country's leading department
stores will remain depressed in the second half of 1998 due to
consumer and corporate belt-tightening to cope with rising
unemployment and the decline in business opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
