<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Small Firms to Receive Supporting Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Small Industry Finance
Corporation of Thailand will extend three billion baht (75 million
U.S. dollars) in loans to help revive thousands of small and
medium-sized enterprises facing severe problems in getting cash,
the Bangkok Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the loans are far from enough as about 200 businesses have
already applied for loans totaling four billion baht (100 million
dollars), according to corporation president Vichien Opasvadhana.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Industry Minister Anurak Chureemas said Wednesday that
each loan would not exceed 50 million baht (1.25 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Small Industry Finance Corporation was established by the
Thai government in a bid to help businesses that could not get
loans from banks.
</P>
<P>
The corporation, which has four branches across the country,
would increase its number of branches and boost staff from 140 to
215 to fill new positions.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that some posts might be filled by staff of
financial institutions who were laid off following the
government's latest financial reform package.
</P>
<P>
Vichien said as part of its business plan for next year, the
corporation would seek a 229 million dollar loan from foreign
financial institutions to help small manufacturers improve the
quality of their products.
</P>
<P>
The corporation was negotiating with some customers to
restructure debt in a bid to reduce non-performing loans that
currently totaled 2.2 billion baht (55 million dollars) or 36
percent of its total lending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
