<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Jumps in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
in July surged 56.8 percent from a year earlier to 1,316.1 billion
yen (about 9.4 billion dollars) due to a decline in imports and
the Japanese yen's weakness against the U.S. dollar, the Finance
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's global imports in July fell 5.7 percent from a year ago
to 3,246.8 billion yen (about 23.1 billion dollars), while exports
rose 6.6 percent to 4,562.9 billion yen (about 32.5 billion
dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Trade surplus with the United States soared 59.7 percent from a
year earlier to 669.7 billion yen (about 4.8 billion dollars), up
for the 22nd consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus with Asian countries fell 36.2 percent to 358.6
billion yen (about 2.6 billion dollars), while that with the
European Union (EU) jumped 174.5 percent to 377.1 billion yen
(about 2.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The average foreign exchange rate used for the July report was
140.42 yen to one U.S. dollar, compared with 114.09 yen a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the July trade report, an economist at a private
financial institution said the Japanese government's comprehensive
economic stimulus measures are likely to prevent a sharp decline
in imports but unlikely to reduce the overall trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus will continue expanding for the time being but
its growth rate is likely to slow down gradually as the positive
effects of the government's stimulus measures are expected to be
seen soon, a ministry official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
