<HEADLINE> Spain to Invest 12 Billion U.S. Dollars in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Spain's investment in
Argentina will reach 12 billion U.S. dollars by 2001,
representatives of 12 major Spanish enterprises in Argentina said
at their meeting with Argentine President Carlos Saul Menem.
</P>
<P>
The money Spain put into Argentina between 1998 and 2001 are
expected to go to sectors including energy, electricity,
communication and construction.
</P>
<P>
Now the biggest Spanish investors in Argentina are the Spanish
Telephone Company, ENDES group, DICASA construction company, and
ASTRA oil company.
</P>
<P>
Spain, the second biggest investor in Argentina, has invested 8
billion dollars in Argentina, amounting to 20 percent of
Argentina's total foregin investment, among which 6.481 billion
dollars were put between 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Menem, aimed at increasing the trade
and investment between the two countries, Spanish representatives
showed their support to Argentina's economic reforms which speeded
up the entry of Spanish investment into Argentina's industry,
finance and service sectors through the privatization process.
</P>
