<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Angola's UNITA Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton has
issued an executive order to impose economic sanctions on
Angola's UNITA movement for non-compliance with its obligations
for peace process, the White House said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The measures taken in the order will immediately demonstrate
to UNITA the seriousness of our concern over its delays in
implementing the peace process," Clinton said in a letter to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Under the executive order, Washington will freeze UNITA assets
in the United States, ban the import of any diamonds not certified
by the government of Angola, and ban the sale of mining equipment.
</P>
<P>
"The blocking of UNITA's property and the other prohibitions
imposed under this executive order will further limit UNITA's
capacity to pay for its military build-up and to undermine the
peace process," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not be lifted until UNITA "fully complies
with its obligations and completes its transition from an armed
movement to an unarmed political party," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
The government of Angola and UNITA signed a peace accord in
Lusaka in 1994, but the trust between the two parties has
recently broken down. And a government spokesman said the peace
process is in "profound crisis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
