<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Re-fixes Export Target at 5.8 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has re-fixed its export
target for the July 1998-June 1999 fiscal year at 5.8 billion U.S.
dollars, about 170 million dollars more than the original target,
to maintain the present annual growth rate of 12.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made Wednesday at a meeting of the Task Force
on Export presided over by Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The export target for the previous fiscal year was fixed at 8.1
billion dollars with an average growth rate of 12.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh achieved an export growth of 16.81 percent during
the last fiscal year and 13.8 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year,
the minister told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Despite economic recession in South Asia, Bangladesh performed
well in export and maintained a high growth rate, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is committed to continuing support to all
genuine exporters, he said. "We are contemplating to provide more
incentives to the exporters for diversifying the export basket and
expanding the volume of export."
</P>
<P>
The minister called upon the exporters and business leaders to
fully utilize the opportunities generated in and outside the
country for bolstering export, saying the government "is very much
sincere in solving the problems which are hindering export
expansion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
