<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Stop Selling Land To Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, Aguest 19 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Minister for
Agriculture and Rural Development Torgyan Jozsef announced
Wednesday that his country will stop selling land to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He told a rally in the small southern city of Opusztaszer that
many foreigners wanted to buy a piece of land in Hungary on the
excuse of European integration.
</P>
<P>
He said that allowing foreigners to own Hungary's land was not
a necessary condition for the country to join the integration
process.
</P>
<P>
The government would take all measures to protect Hungary's
land from falling into the hands of foreigners as it was the
resources of famers based on which they could improve their life,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, about 80 percent of Hungary's state
enterprises have been sold to foreigners in the process of
privatization, together with large pieces of land in the western
areas.
</P>
<P>
The former government had planed to legalize the land selling,
but met strong opposition from the farmers, who raised the slogan
that "selling land means betraying the country."
</P>
<P>
The new government supports the farmers by revising the stance
of its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
The minister pledged that the government would make all efforts
to promote the development in under-developed areas, including
support to small and medium-sized enterprises, the agricultural
products processing industry and animal husbandry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
