<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Introduce Child Protection Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will introduce a
National Child Protection Authority Act to protect children's
rights, sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the legislation will be presented in
Parliament Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This is considered one of the most important pieces of
legislation which will fill in the gaps in the existing law on the
rights of children and child abuse, Minister of Justice G. L.
Pieris was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister earlier said the legislation will introduce
several new offenses into the penal code, concerning the
employment of children for begging and other undue pressures
brought to children and youth at work places.
</P>
<P>
Penalties are to be increased and minimum mandatory penalties
will be introduced for some offenses, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The legislation also ensures the right to education.
</P>
<P>
The legislation has received the consensus of all parties
represented in Parliament as a desperately required measure, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
