<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Real Estate Prices in Thailand Attract Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Several multinational companies
have set up a regional trade and investment office in Thailand due
to the currency depreciation and lower real estate prices here, a
Board of Investment (BoI) press release available Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
BoI has approved 30 companies' requests to establish trade and
investment offices during the first half of the year. These firms
included major corporations such as Isuzu Motor, Waste Management,
NEC, and Nova Gas, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
To compete with Singapore and Malaysia in luring multinational
firms to establish regional offices, the BoI has been providing
non-tax incentives since January 1996 and has already had about 90
projects under this category.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, four companies, namely Makro Asia Management,
Art Chemical (Thailand), EEC Lincoln Scott and Yaskawa Engineering
Asia Pacific, received approval under this category.
</P>
<P>
BoI said the depreciation of the baht and the cheaper real
estate and rental prices, which have helped reduce the cost of
doing business in Thailand, are the main reasons for the
increasing interest of foreign firms in locating their regional
offices in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Air France moved its regional headquarters from
Hong Kong to Bangkok, while the Pacific Asia Travel Association
announced it would move its head office to Bangkok from San
Francisco this September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
