<HEADLINE> Deer Saved From Rising Flood Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The central government has
decided to allocate a special fund of 800,000 yuan (96,000 US
dollars) to protect deer threatened by rising flood waters in
Shishou Pere David's Nature Reserve in Hubei Province, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
This has been confirmed yesterday by sources with the State
Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, which will soon be raised to the level of a
national nature reserve, is now home to 130 Pere David's deer, a
rare breed imported from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to prompt protective action, all the deer have survived
the floods and are now living safely on an isolated island.
</P>
<P>
The provincial environmental protection bureau opened a special
hotline to the nature reserve to be used in case of
emergency. Every day, local farmers cut grass and transport it to
the island to feed the deer.
</P>
<P>
The battle to preserve the conservation farm for white-fin
dolphin in Tongling, Anhui Province, has also been crowned with
success.
</P>
<P>
The farm, built in 1994 with an investment of over 10 million
yuan, aims to protect the 100 dolphins -- a species unique to the
Yangtze River -- and help increase number.
</P>
<P>
To better protect nature reserves and preserve rare animals and
plants, the State Council released a notice this week asking local
governments to tighten management of nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
The notice stipulates that tourism and production activities
will be banned in the buffer-zone areas of nature reserves
nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
