<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Suffers Losses Due to World Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Brazil has lost more than
2.5 billion U.S. dollars so far this month in the wake of the
international financial crisis and the latest ruble devaluation, the
Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper based its report on figures released by the
Central Bank of Brazil and non-official data on the currency
exchange transactions in Brazil up to last Monday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the bank's International Reserves Department Maria Do
Socorro Carvalho attributed the loss to frozen credits and the
outflow of foreign money from Brazilian banks because of lower
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
She noted that investors now hesitated about putting their
money on risky projects.
</P>
<P>
However, Central Bank President Gustavo Franco affirmed that
the government is not worried about repaying foreign debts as it
has enough foreign reserves, which, according to the bank, stand
at 71 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
