<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Regulations On Human Genomes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China has issued regulations to
restricting the removal of human genome resources from China and
encouraging Sino-overseas cooperation in genetics under a
principle of shared intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Human organs, tissues, cells, blood and related materials
should not be transported outside China without permission from
the Ministry of Science and Technology. The Ministry's human
genome management office is responsible for this and will look
into the technical and financial power of Chinese and foreign
research groups and the ownership and sharing of the intellectual
property rights.
</P>
<P>
The office requires a certificate of informed consent from
providers of human genetic materials and their family members to
guarantee the quality of international cooperation and to protect
both sides, according to a Ministry official who participated in
drafting the regulation, but asked not to be identified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Riot Probe Team to Query Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's government-created
Combined Fact-Finding Team plans to question a number of security
commanders about the riots in Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, and
other cities in mid-May, a statement issued by the team said.
</P>
<P>
"The team will soon interview officials who were in charge of
security during the riots to obtain clarification," the 19-member
team which was established on July 23 said in the statement
available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team's chairman Marzuki Darusman said details about the
security commanders or when they would be questioned would be
finalized on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A source close to the investigation said that former Jakarta
military commander Maj. Gen. Sjafrie Sjamsoeddin and former city
police chief Maj. Gen. Hamami Nata were among those to be
questioned, Jakarta Post daily reported.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,200 died in the May 13-15 riots in Jakarta and other
cities and thousands of buildings were looted or burned.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported later that women, primarily of Chinese
descent, became victims of rape and sexual abuse during the riots.
</P>
<P>
Activists, including members of the Volunteers for Humanity led
by Catholic priest Sandyawan Sumardi, have reported that 168 women
were raped or sexually assaulted between May 13 and July 3.
</P>
<P>
The fact-finding team, which comprises representatives from the
Armed Forces, government agencies, the National Commission on
Human Rights and non-governmental organizations (NGOs), is charged
with the task of investigating and, if possible, unveiling the
perpetrators of the riots, which some say were organized.
</P>
<P>
The joint team is expected to complete its task in three
months.
</P>
<P>
The team criticized officials Wednesday for voicing doubts
about reports of rapes and sexual assaults during the riots.
</P>
<P>
National Police Chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi said Monday that
some NGOs had exaggerated such reports. He warned that if the NGOs
failed to come up with evidence and continued alleging that sexual
assaults occurred, they could be charged for spreading
unsubstantiated rumors.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki said Roesmanhadi's remarks "only hamper the team's
work," He said. "With certainty, I confirm that there are facts
(about the rapes)."
</P>
<P>
He said the team had completed collecting information and was
now in its "verification" stage.
</P>
<P>
"Government officials should not make intimidating and
contradicting statements before the task force finishes its job,"
said team member Saparinah Sadli.
</P>
<P>
The National Commission on Human Rights argued last month that
the reported sexual assaults during the riots were perpetrated
systematically by an unidentified group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Genome (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Before the regulations appeared, some foreigners and
enterprises took genetic disease materials out of China without
permission and many Chinese scientists have been worried about the
drain on human genetic resources and have written letters to
national leaders.
</P>
<P>
They say that China should protect human genome resources,
which are essential to future developments in the pharmaceutical
and health care industries and that the protective methods will
not affect cooperation with foreign scientists.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are looking for more opportunities for international
cooperation, and the regulations are not going to be a barrier,
according to Qiang Boqin, vice-president of the Chinese Academy of
Medical Sciences and director of the Beijing Human Genome Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
China has a large population and many ethnic groups and some
genetic diseases have developed that have long been separated from
the outside world but the increasing transient population has
reduced the amount of genetic resources.
</P>
<P>
Genetic research in China is still undeveloped and should be
open to international cooperation based on equality of
responsibility, Professor Chen Zhu, director of the Shanghai Human
Genome Research Center, says.
</P>
<P>
There are now 30 laboratories in China involved in human genome
research, and two gene sequencing centers will be set up in
Beijing and Shanghai as part of the global Human Genome Project,
and genetic research on leukemia and liver, stomach, and esophagus
cancers, high blood pressure, and other major diseases has already
reached a high level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
