<HEADLINE> Giant 6,000-year-old Sculpture Discovered In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Two very large 6,000-year-old
sculptures have been unearthed in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, establishing a connection here of early people with fish
and dragon images.
</P>
<P>
A team of archeologists discovered the fish and dragon, which
are made of earth, in a 4-meter-deep, 8-meter-wide trench that is
45 meters long.
</P>
<P>
One eye socket of the dragon has human remains in a kneeling
position, with his hands behind his back. Archeologists say that
he may have been a prisoner of war or the chief of an enemy tribe
who was killed at a sacrificial ceremony.
</P>
<P>
They also found remains of houses and ash pits near the trench,
which is located at the junction of the Yellow and the Hun rivers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
