<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building 20 More Power Stations On Yalong River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build 20 more
power stations on the Yalong River, a tributary of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The 1,517-kilometer-long Yalong drops more than 4,400 meters
along its course and is ideal for power stations.
</P>
<P>
The plan is for 21 power stations with a combined capacity of
23.7 billion kwh in Sichuan Province in southwestern China. A
large amount has been spent on geological studies and dam site
selection, according to Liu Junfeng, general manager of the Ertan
Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are now under way for the Guandi Hydroelectric
Power Station, with a designed generating capacity of
1.8 million kwh.
</P>
<P>
A previous station, the Ertan facility, has a designed capacity
of 3.3 million kwh and is the largest hydroelectric power station
completed in China this century.
</P>
<P>
The Yalong River valley is one of China's 12 major
hydroelectric power development areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
