<HEADLINE> Southeastern Chinese Police Tighten Down On Illegal Border Crossing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of attempts to cross
the border in China's coastal province of Fujian illegally for
purposes of emigration are down this year because of a crackdown
by border police.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, police successfully stopped 60
illegal border crossings in the first seven months of the year,
involving some 660 people.
</P>
<P>
A number of coastal cities and counties in Fujian have been
used by a "snakehead", an organizer of illegal border crossings,
as a departure point for illegal emigration to Japan, the United
States and other countries. To stop the illegal border crossings,
border police have worked out an information network and reporting
system, which helped them arrest 59 snakeheads in the January-July
period.
</P>
<P>
They have also increased inspections and checks in a dozen of
counties and towns that are notorious for illegal border crossing
activities.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts have got support from police in other provinces
and cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
