<HEADLINE> New Czech Cabinet Survives Vote of Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Czech cabinet led by Premier
Milos Zeman survived a vote of confidence in parliament Wednesday
with 73 favorable votes, 39 negative and 24 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
A simple majority of 69 of the 136 deputies present was
required to endorse the motion of confidence in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
All the 73 deputies from Zeman's Social Democrats present at
the ballot voted in favor of the cabinet while the 39
parliamentary members from the Liberal Party and the Christian
Democratic Union-People's Party voted against it.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four deputies from the Communist Party of the Czech and
Moravia abstained from the voting. As agreed upon earlier,
deputies from the Civic Democratic Party (ODS) led by Vaclav Klaus
walked out of the conference hall prior to the vote.
</P>
<P>
Zeman's one-party minority cabinet was appointed by Present
Vaclav Havel on July 22.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal struck with Zeman before the cabinet formation,
parliament speaker Klaus, hitherto Zeman's arch political rival,
would lead his 63 deputies out of the Chamber of Deputies to
ensure the new cabinet's survival in the vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
In return for its tacit support, the ODS will take the key post
of chamber chairmanship, to be in a position to set the
government's legislative agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
