<HEADLINE> 8 Dutchmen, 2 Britons Detained for Money Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian police have detained
eight Dutchmen and two Britons for an alleged attempt to smuggle
1.6 million U.S. dollars out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Five of the Dutchmen and one Briton were arrested with the
money at Sofia Airport before boarding a Frankfurt-bound plane, a
Bulgarian police chief said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a following search the police seized another one million
U.S. dollars, said Milcho Yashev, deputy director of the national
police.
</P>
<P>
The sum was a part of a four-million-U.S. dollar transfer from
the Dutch Rabo Bank to the account of Van Seidenfeld Cornelis, a
Dutchman, with the United Bulgarian Bank.
</P>
<P>
Cornelis is believed to have withdrawn the sum and distributed
it to the six people who were apprehended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Another three Dutchmen and one Briton who were also connected
to the case were apprehended outside Sofia, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
Police were following various leads including connections to
money laundering, said Yashev.
</P>
<P>
Under the Bulgarian Criminal Code, the detainees will be
charged for violations of regulations on transactions in currency
assets and the obligation to declare such assets to customs. They
could be sentenced to up to six years' imprisonment or be fined
double the sum they tried to traffic illegally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
