<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Patrols with U.S. Need Authorization. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican
Attorney-General stressed on Wednesday that joint patrols with the
United States on Costa Rican waters will only be possible with
legislative authorization.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been insisting since 1997 on establishing
a joint patrol surveillance program, in order to combat drug
trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, the Costa Rican constitution prohibits the entrance of
foreign armed vessels into its territories, without a previous
authorization by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the U.S. requests can not be accepted until a
resolution is passed by the Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney-General is advising the government to work on a
long term permission for joint patrols for approval of the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The measure has been looked on favorably in the assembly, where
different opposition sectors have nodded their agreement, as long
as certain conditions are met, like putting a Costa Rican in
command of the patrols.
</P>
<P>
However there are people who disagree with the plan, and they
think that it would not help the fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Central America and the Caribbean are believed to be transit
zones for the drugs produced in Colombia, which are destined for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors are saying that it would be better if Costa Rica
patrols the area by itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
