<HEADLINE> UEFA Set to Challenge Super League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA is set to discuss changes to the format of their three
European club competitions in a bid to challenge the threat of a
breakaway Super League.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago Manchester United and Arsenal confirmed they had
been involved in talks about joining a new 32-team league to
kick-off in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Such proposals have aroused serious concern at both the
Football Association and Premier League, while FIFA president,
Sepp Blatter, has urged clubs to halt all Super League
discussions.
</P>
<P>
Apparent plans, which are still in the consultative stage,
include increasing the number of teams in the Champions' League
from 24 to 32 and merging the Cup Winners' Cup and UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
A UEFA spokesman said: "We are still talking with clubs and
associations with regards to any new proposals."
</P>
<P>
"But the executive committee meets on August 29 in Monaco and
of course the Super League will be one of the topics under
discussion. A press conference is planned for after the meeting,
" the spokesman added. 
</P>
