<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Supports Goods-for-Guns Program in El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Wednesday that
It will contribute 130,000 Canadian dollars (85,800 U.S. dollars)
to support a "Goods for Guns" program in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
The project sets out to tackle the problem of the proliferation
of small arms and contribute to building an enduring peace in this
post-conflict country.
</P>
<P>
Funded through the Peacebuilding Fund, the program is designed
to offer viable alternatives to former combatants by supporting an
exchange of weapons for coupons redeemable for consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy made the
announcement in Orillia, Canada, where he was participating in an
international meeting of non-governmental organizations (NGOS) on
the proliferation of small arms.
</P>
<P>
"The most pressing need is humanitarian action to help
societies that are emerging from conflict and are awash with small
arms," said the Canadian minister at the meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no single solution. Instead, the issue needs to be
tackled by concurrently taking global, regional and national
approaches. We must consider action to stop the accumulation of
these weapons, which contribute to regional instability and
domestic conflicts while also causing considerable human
suffering," added Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
This initiative is the result of cooperation between Salvadoran
businessmen and members of the Rotary Club of El Salvador and
Rotary International who joined forces to fight the rise of armed
crime in El Salvador over the past years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
