<HEADLINE> Highlights of today's major Beijing-based newspapers: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The battle against the worst flooding in decades has reached
a crucial moment, with surging flood water inundating China's
largest oilfield in the northeast and the sixth flood crest
forming on the Yangtze River in the south.
</P>
<P>
Millions of weary civilians and soldiers continue to battle
flooding and additional military units are being deployed to
assist in the effort.
</P>
<P>
-- The Red Cross Society of China (RCSC) has urged its local
branches to enhance efforts to prevent any possible outbreaks of
disease in the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Flood-relief donations across the country have gone up to
1.6 billion yuan (195 million U.S. dollars), officials in charge
of the relief work said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Though millions of Chinese flood victims are homeless, their
basic daily needs have been ensured, according to government
officials.
</P>
<P>
-- This year's sixth Yangtze River flood crest yesterday met
the flood waters of Dongting Lake, and water levels of the lake
and the Yangtze, from Lianhuatang to Wuhan, rose to new record
highs.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's lawmakers are working on the country's first unified
contract law, a top legislator said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
