<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Foresees 1 Percent GNP Growth for Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has forecast the Philippines would be fortunate if its gross
national product (GNP) grows 1 percent this year, considering the
poor results of the agriculture sector and the barrage of external
shocks.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines "will be lucky if we still have positive (GNP)
growth of up to 1 percent this year," the Business World on
Thursday quoted IMF representative to Manila Henri Lorie as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has adjusted its GNP growth target to
2-3 percent from the original 3-4 percent; gross domestic product
(GDP) growth to 1.5-2.5 percent from 2.5-3 percent; and inflation
to 9.25-9.75 percent from the previous 7.5-8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
GNP represents the value of the country's output of goods and
services, including income from abroad. GDP does not include the
income from abroad.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had prescribed a 3-4 percent 1998 GNP growth when it
sealed a two-year precautionary agreement with Manila last March,
giving the country access to a 1.37 billion-dollar emergency fund
facility.
</P>
<P>
Lorie said the macro-economic and fiscal targets have to be
revised down considering the disappointing performance of the
agriculture sector and the lingering regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the country's agricultural
output dropped by a substantial 7.15 percent, the worst record in
the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lorie said the IMF can tolerate a deficit in the
fiscal position of the Philippine government in the light of the
economic slowdown hovering in the region.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said earlier that the IMF
has conceded to a 40-billion-peso (930 million U.S. dollars)
budget deficit this year, a turnaround from the earlier commitment
of a 5-billion-peso (116 million dollars) surplus.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is now preparing for the upcoming review of the
economy by an IMF mission beginning August 26.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the ongoing financial crisis and the El Nino,
the country's GNP grew 2.5 percent in the first quarter this year
while GDP increased by 1.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
