<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Loans Shrink Sharply in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' bank loans
growth rate slowed down to only 10.4 percent at end-June this year
compared to the year-ago 36.3 percent, Journal reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting data from the central bank, said the drop
in loans reflects the prevailing pessimism of banks on the economy
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"This confirms the view point that banks still see much risk in
lending activities despite our efforts to mitigate the impact of
the financial crisis," a high-ranking central bank official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the loans growth rate has been declining since the
regional financial crisis first started in Thailand in July last
year.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the growth rate hit the bottom at 10.1
percent, going hand in hand with the slowdown of the economy
battered by the El Nino weather phenomenon and the surge of
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The rate of 10.4 percent only reflected an insignificant
increase from end-May, which the official attributed to attempts
by authorities to put some confidence back in the market.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in the first half this year, 30 percent
of the total loans were extended to the manufacturing sector, 26
percent to financial institutions, real estate and business
services sector, 15 percent to the wholesale and retail trade
business, and the rest to agriculture, mining, construction,
transportation and other sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
