<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Two U.S.-made Iridium Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A China-made Long March 2C
carrier rocket successfully sent two U.S.-made iridium satellites
early this morning into pre-set orbit from the Taiyuan Satellite
Launching Center in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The rocket lifted off from the center at 7:01 a.m. today
(Beijing time).
</P>
<P>
China has fulfilled all contracted launching tasks of the
iridium satellites into orbits. The current launch of the iridiums,
made by the Motorola Corp. of the United States, aims to make up
the communication satellite network.
</P>
<P>
Initial data from the Xi'an Satellite Monitoring and Control
Center indicated that the distributor of the satellites separated
the second stage of the rocket and entered its parking orbit 11
minutes after launch.
</P>
<P>
Sliding for 40 minutes, the distributor successfully altered
course, and boosted the two satellites into their predetermined
orbit at a perigee of 612.35 km, an apogee of 635.48 km, and a
bank angle of 86.4 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The launch had been originally arranged in mid-July and was put
off upon the request of the United States firm due to technical
factors of the satellites.
</P>
<P>
The three-stage Long March 2C carrier rocket, designed
especially to launch iridium satellites, is 40 meters long, 3.35
meters in diameter and weighes 213 tons when launched. The rocket
has been used in five successful launches.
</P>
<P>
The iridium satellite system developed by Motorola is a global
wireless communications network that will combine the worldwide
reach of 66 low-earth-orbit satellites with land-based wireless
systems. The 66 satellites are supposed to be placed in orbit 780
kilometers above the earth at six levels and to be sent into space
by carrier rockets manufactured in the United States, Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
With the cooperation of the Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center and
the Chinese Academy of Carrier Rocket Technology, the China Great
Wall Industry Corp. fulfilled the launching contract of six
iridium satellites from December of 1997 to May of this year. It
will carry out a number of launches to make up the satellite
network in the future.
</P>
<P>
Today's launch was the 54th flight of the Long March family of
rockets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Reorganization Needed for Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Further re-organization of the
government system towards a single decision center is the only way
to encourage economic growth in Italy, the Audit Court said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Industry Ministry, for example, should be entrusted with
the power of coordinating policies designed to promote the
"enterprise system", said the court in its annual report to the
Industry Ministry.
</P>
<P>
That would mean putting industrial policies under the same roof
as some responsibilities currently held by the Foreign Trade
Ministry, the Ministry for Agricultural Resources and the
Treasury, the court said.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has already taken measures to
streamline its frameworks and the Treasury had been merged with
the Budget Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a plan was unveiled to group a whole range
of scattered cultural responsibilities in a single ministry, and
another proposal recommended merging the Industry and Labour
ministries as the only way of combating the soaring unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The Audit Court also said that a single agency was needed to
coordinate various agreements designed to trigger growth in
specific zones, and to strike a balance between the regulatory and
policy making functions of the government.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts believed economic development policies were
rarely effective if they were fragmented between a number of
ministries and, the court noted, fragmentation of government
powers meant scattered and wasted resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
