Angeles Lakers assistant Kurt Rambis, according to a press report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Los Angeles Times said that the Clippers will make a
formal offer to Rambis, who has been a Lakers assistant the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
However, the Sacramento Kings may also be interested in Rambis
after they fired coach Eddie Jordan on Tuesday. The Clippers
refuse to comment on any report regarding their coaching search.
</P>
<P>
The Clippers have been searching for a coach since April 20
when they fired Bill Fitch, the second-winningest and all-time
losingest coach in NBA history, after a 17-65 season. Los Angeles
reached the playoffs the previous season under Fitch.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old Rambis is best known for his hard-nosed style
of playing in a 14-year NBA career, including nine with the
Lakers. After helping the Lakers win back-to-back titles in 1987
and 1988, Rambis signed as an unrestricted free agent with the
Charlotte Hornets. He also played with the Phoenix Suns and the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
After scored the second-worst record in the Western Conference
in 1997-98, the Clippers will attempt to rebuild with Michael
Olowokandi, the first pick in the 1998 draft, and forward Maurice
Taylor, a first round pick in 1997. 
</P>
