<HEADLINE> Sampras Advances in Pilot Pen Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras of the United
States ousted Australian teenager Lleyton Hewitt 6-1, 7-6 (7-4)
in the second round of the 745,000 U.S. dollars Pilot Pen tennis
tournament in Connecticut of the United States Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, the top seed, could have ended Marcelo Rios' one-week
reign as the top-ranked player by winning Sunday's ATP
championship final, but squandered the opportunity when he lost
in three sets to Patrick Rafter of Australian in a match that
still rankles him.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously with what happened on Sunday, I'm still thinking
about it," said Sampras, who believed that Rafter's serve on
match point was out.
</P>
<P>
"It's a tough way to lose that match. I lost the second set
and had some chances in the third but the chair umpire overruled
that match point. I was very upset."
</P>
<P>
This week's rankings have Sampras 41 points behind Chile's
Rios, who is playing in the RCA championships at Indianapolis.
The rankings, released next Monday, most likely will be the basis
for seedings for the U.S. Open later this month. Both this event
and the Indianapolis tournament offer a base of 260 points.
</P>
<P>
Rafter is also in the hunt for the top spot. He needs to win
and collect enough bonus points while Sampras and Rios fail to
reach the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's other matches, Australian Open champion and
third seed Petr Korda of the Czech Republic beat Ukrainian Andrei
Medvedev 6-3,2-6, 6-1. Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov defeated
Australian Todd Woodbridge 6-0, 6-2. Sixth seed Tim Henman of
Britain dismissed Italian Vincenzo Santopadre 6-2, 6-3. Seventh
seed Karol Kucera of Slovakia downed Argentina's Hernan Gumy 6-3,
6-3, and eighth seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia got past
American Geoff Grant 6-3, 3-6,6-3.  
</P>
