<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Win World's Top Maths Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Two British professors from the
University of Cambridge have received prestigious Feilds Awards,
the mathematical equivalent of Nobel Prizes.
</P>
<P>
Richard Borcherds, 38, and Tim Gowers, 34, are among four
winners announced at the International Congress of Mathematicians
in Berlin, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Britain has won two of the medals,
which are named after Canadian mathematician Joseph Fields and
awarded every four years since 1936 only to academics under the
age of 40.
</P>
<P>
Another British mathematician, Professor Andrew Wiles, 45, who
solved the mathematical mystery of Fermat's Last Theorem but was
too old to qualify for a medal, was also given a special award at
the Berlin Congress.
</P>
<P>
Peter Mandelson, the British cabinet minister with special
responsibility for science and technology, said in a statement
that he was "delighted" that British scientists have been awarded
the world's top maths prize.
</P>
<P>
"These awards speak for the continuing vigor of British
mathematics, and I hope they will inspire more of our young people
to pursue the subject at school and university," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Non-U.S. Web Users to Skyrocket by2002: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 19 (Xinhua) -- There will be approximately
100 million Web users in the world by the end of this year and 320
million by 2002, according to a new study of the U.S. research
firm International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
In the new report on the global market forecast for Internet
usage and commerce, IDC said that the number of non-U.S. users of
the World Wide Web will increase more quickly over the next four
years than the number of their U.S. counterparts.
</P>
<P>
While the growth of Web users and Internet access devices will
remain steady in the U.S., the real explosion in numbers will
occur in the Asia-Pacific region between 1997 and 2002. Other
areas outside the U.S. will also experience high growth, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
IDC said that there were 78.1 million devices used to access
the Web in 1997 worldwide. This number will jump to 515 million by
2002.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, there were 18 million people using the Internet for
shopping worldwide, the IDC report said, and the number will
increase dramatically to reach 128 million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Due to the huge increase in the number of Web shoppers, IDC
predicted that more than 400 billion U.S. dollars worth of goods
and services will change hands over the Internet by 2002, a
compound annual growth rate of 103 percent between 1997 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the percentage of worldwide users buying good on the
Internet will increase from 26 percent in December 1997 to 40
percent in December 2002, IDC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Provides More Assistance to China's Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Wednesday that
it will provide 200,000 Canadian dollars (132,000 U.S. dollars) in
additional emergency relief aid to flood victims in China.
</P>
<P>
"An estimated 240 million people in north, central and south
east China -- one fifth of China's population -- are affected by
what is being described as the worst floods in living memory,"
said International Cooperation Minister Diane Marleau in a
release.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians are deeply moved by the suffering caused by this
devastating natural disaster," added the minister.
</P>
<P>
The aid package provided by the Canadian International
Development Agency (CIDA) will support the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies in their
efforts to help the people most affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Red Cross is providing an additional 160,000
Canadian dollars of public contributions. This brings its total
contribution to 310,000 Canadian dollars (204,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The CIDA's additional contribution, along with that of the
Canadian Red Cross, brings Canada's total humanitarian assistance
for China's flood victims to 560,000 Canadian dollars (369,600
U.S. dollars). The CIDA contributed 50,000 Canadian dollars in
July following an appeal to the international community by the
federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
