<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Show Americans Still Support Clinton as President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Americans continue to approve
of the job President Bill Clinton is doing and want the Monica
Lewinsky probe to end but may become less lenient if more damaging
information comes out, polls showed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A CBS News/New York Times poll showed 71 percent of those asked
approved of the job Clinton is doing as president, up four
percentage points from a week ago. Twenty-seven percent
disapproved.
</P>
<P>
By three-to-one, the public think the Lewinsky investigation
should be dropped now that Clinton admitted the affair, but half
said resignation or impeachment would be the answer if it comes
out that Clinton asked Lewinsky to lie about it. Forty-eight
percent believe he did just that.
</P>
<P>
But CBS said, "For the first time since this question was asked
in late January, people are more likely to blame Clinton himself
for creating the current situation than to blame his political
enemies."
</P>
<P>
A poll conducted by Zogby International showed Clinton with a
personal approval rating of 54.4 percent against unfavorable of
43.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
That was different from the 61.2 percent approval rate in July
compared to 35.9 percent unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
But 47 percent said they did not believe Clinton when he denied
encouraging anyone to lie and 65 percent said if he did he should
consider leaving office.
</P>
<P>
"The president is not out of the woods. Americans do not appear
to be satisfied with his speech," pollster John Zogby said. "While
his ability to govern has not been damaged too severely, for the
first time we are seeing majorities favoring the possibility of
his leaving office."
</P>
<P>
A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll had Clinton's job approval rating
at 66 percent, versus 29 percent who disapproved, about the same
as a week ago, but his personal approval rating stood more than 20
percentage points below his job rating.
</P>
<P>
Only 29 percent said they thought Clinton was completely open
and honest in his Monday speech while 61 percent said he tried to
mislead the public on some matters. Ten percent said they used to
support Clinton but no longer do.
</P>
<P>
But in some good news for the White House, when asked by the
Gallup poll as to whom they blamed for events getting to where
they are now, 39 percent said Clinton and 44 percent said
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen percent in the Gallup poll said events of the past few
days made it more likely they would vote for Republican candidates
this fall but 12 percent said they were more likely to vote for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The CBS and CNN polls had margins of error of four percentage
points and Zogby had one of 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Polls conducted immediately after an event are not always a
reliable gauge of what will happen later, said Andrew Kohut,
director of the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes delayed reactions are substantially different from
initial reactions," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
