<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, India Stand Out in Declining Asian PC Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Personal computer shipments
in China and India gained strong growth during the first quarter,
although the Asia-pacific region continued to falter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. research firm International Data Corporation (IDC)
said Wednesday that PC shipments in the region, which exclude
Japan, dropped 5 percent, below its initial forecast of a 1.4
percent decrease. But China and India stood out with 28 percent
and 39 percent growth respectively.
</P>
<P>
Also in the second quarter, IDC said, revenue for PC makers
fell 35 percent in the region. The sharp decline in revenue was
caused by many of the same factors as experienced in the first
quarter: the popularity of PCs priced around 1,000 U.S. dollars,
price sensitivity due to Asia's economic crisis and the increasing
market share taken by India and China, where systems were priced
lower than in the more developed markets.
</P>
<P>
IDC said that U.S. PC makers Compaq, IBM and Hewlett-Packard
maintained the region's top three vendors during the second
quarter. China's Lengend climbed to the fourth rank in the
regional market for the first time due to healthy growth in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The worst market conditions remained in Southeast Asia and
South Korea in the second quarter, IDC said. Indonesia, Thailand
and South Korea recorded the steepest shipment declines from the
previous year with decreases of 90 percent, 40 percent and 58
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
China remained the region's largest market, accounting for 39
percent of total unit shipments during the period, IDC said. PC
shipments in China increased 28 percent from a year ago to reach
nearly 1 million units.
</P>
<P>
India's growth was strong in the second quarter and it produced
the greatest annual growth rate in the region with shipments up 39
percent from a year ago. Australia, with a 12 percent growth,
continued to be the second largest market in the region after
surpassing South Korea for the position in the first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
