<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Meets Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Wednesday were considering a draft statement on
Kosovo, the council president, Danilo Turk, said.
</P>
<P>
Turk told reporters that "the consultations are continuing" so
that different ideas could "be reflected further."
</P>
<P>
The consultations came as efforts were being made to bring the
two sides of Kosovo back to the negotiating table to end six
months of conflicts, which have caused more than 500 deaths and
created about 200,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, the 15-member Security Council called for an
immediate cease-fire between the security force of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia and the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Turk said that the issue of Kosovo "can
have no military solution."
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, Serbia's southernmost province, has an area of some
10,000 square kilometers and a population of more than 2 million,
of whom 90 percent are ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
