<DOCNO> XIE19980820.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stld Jordan's King Reshuffles Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's official Petra news
agency Wednesday said Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali is to
present his resignation and Chief of Royal Court Fayez Tarawneh is
expected to be entrusted to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Petra retracted its earlier urgent dispatch, saying
the king, who has been in the U.S. for treatment for cancer, has
accepted Majali's resignation and named Tarawneh to for a new
administration.
</P>
<P>
In fact this did not make much difference. Analysts here said
Petra's dramatic change of tone only reflected the delicate
political situation in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh has a strong link with the royal family. His father,
Ahmad Tarawneh, who died on August 8, once served as deputy prime
minister, parliament member and chief of Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh was ambassador to the United States, and he negotiated
the peace treaty with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A new government is expected to be announced within days.
</P>
<P>
Majali's government has been under fire for negligence in
handling the polluted drinking water incident and mismanagement of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Local papers Tuesday quoted government officials as saying
that a cabinet reshuffle might come next week, when seven to 12
ministers will be purged but Majali will not step down until the
king comes back.
</P>
<P>
The ministers to be sacked were said to bear the responsibility
for water pollution in west Amman, a recent collision of two jumbo
jets in Jordan's airspace and an explosion at the Aqaba power
plant near the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Majali government also fell short of expectations in
pushing through reforms, such as privatizing state-own companies,
combating poverty and unemployment, supervising parliamentary
elections, and improving the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
